00:00:09.980 --> 00:00:27.511 align:middle line:90%


00:00:27.511 --> 00:00:29.260 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA MEREDITH: In
my last conversation

00:00:29.260 --> 00:00:31.980 align:middle line:10%
with Randall Carlson, we
discussed the ancient meaning

00:00:31.980 --> 00:00:34.320 align:middle line:10%
behind some of the more
well-known numbers used

00:00:34.320 --> 00:00:35.530 align:middle line:10%
in sacred texts.

00:00:35.530 --> 00:00:38.490 align:middle line:84%
Today we're going to look at
how those numbers, geometry,

00:00:38.490 --> 00:00:41.550 align:middle line:84%
geology, and sacred and
mystical architecture

00:00:41.550 --> 00:00:45.220 align:middle line:84%
tell us about our human
history, both past and future.

00:00:45.220 --> 00:00:47.520 align:middle line:84%
And that goes to some
pretty grim places

00:00:47.520 --> 00:00:49.240 align:middle line:84%
in terms of the
human experience,

00:00:49.240 --> 00:00:52.280 align:middle line:84%
in terms of catastrophe,
cycles of catastrophe.

00:00:52.280 --> 00:00:56.160 align:middle line:84%
And I just want to say we ended
our last show talking I said,

00:00:56.160 --> 00:00:57.760 align:middle line:90%
so what's up with 666?

00:00:57.760 --> 00:01:00.110 align:middle line:84%
How did it get this
beastly connotation?

00:01:00.110 --> 00:01:01.660 align:middle line:84%
And that led us to
the conversation.

00:01:01.660 --> 00:01:04.286 align:middle line:84%
You said, well, it's classically
always connected with the sun.

00:01:04.286 --> 00:01:05.243 align:middle line:90%
>>RANDALL CARLSON: Yes.

00:01:05.243 --> 00:01:07.460 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: How can the sun
have a beastly connotation?

00:01:07.460 --> 00:01:10.060 align:middle line:84%
And that's where we
left our conversation.

00:01:10.060 --> 00:01:13.190 align:middle line:10%
>>CARLSON: Well, it brings us
to the idea of a variable sun.

00:01:13.190 --> 00:01:15.860 align:middle line:10%
Now, this is something that's
been very controversial

00:01:15.860 --> 00:01:19.980 align:middle line:10%
within scientific circles
and is by no means accepted.

00:01:19.980 --> 00:01:22.680 align:middle line:84%
And particularly
these days, there's

00:01:22.680 --> 00:01:28.350 align:middle line:84%
been a-- I'll call it an
agenda to dismiss any evidence

00:01:28.350 --> 00:01:30.000 align:middle line:90%
for a variable sun.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:33.650 align:middle line:10%
Because once we recognize
that the sun may

00:01:33.650 --> 00:01:39.630 align:middle line:10%
vary in its intensity or what
Jay Widener has been working

00:01:39.630 --> 00:01:42.980 align:middle line:10%
with is the idea of
coronal mass ejections-

00:01:42.980 --> 00:01:47.279 align:middle line:10%
that was the subject of
Robert Schoch's last book.

00:01:47.279 --> 00:01:49.320 align:middle line:10%
I think there's a considerable
amount of evidence

00:01:49.320 --> 00:01:52.070 align:middle line:10%
that supports the idea
of a variable sun.

00:01:52.070 --> 00:01:55.980 align:middle line:84%
Of course, that goes contrary
to some of the agendas today

00:01:55.980 --> 00:01:58.730 align:middle line:84%
that are attempting to dismiss
the influence of the sun

00:01:58.730 --> 00:02:01.390 align:middle line:84%
as far as questions
of climate change.

00:02:01.390 --> 00:02:03.459 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Oh, that
becomes very political.

00:02:03.459 --> 00:02:04.250 align:middle line:90%
>>CARLSON: It does.

00:02:04.250 --> 00:02:06.041 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: We've got
carbon tax credits that

00:02:06.041 --> 00:02:08.830 align:middle line:84%
need to be allocated and
people who benefit from those.

00:02:08.830 --> 00:02:11.160 align:middle line:84%
And so that's a
political agenda.

00:02:11.160 --> 00:02:12.870 align:middle line:90%
>>CARLSON: Yes.

00:02:12.870 --> 00:02:15.150 align:middle line:84%
But I think that
there's enough evidence

00:02:15.150 --> 00:02:19.560 align:middle line:84%
out there, both from the hard
scientific realm but also

00:02:19.560 --> 00:02:24.440 align:middle line:84%
from the archaic traditions,
to suggest that the sun has

00:02:24.440 --> 00:02:26.110 align:middle line:84%
a degree of
variability that could

00:02:26.110 --> 00:02:30.270 align:middle line:84%
have considerable consequences
for life on Earth.

00:02:30.270 --> 00:02:34.390 align:middle line:10%
And so I think that if
we're talking about 666

00:02:34.390 --> 00:02:37.720 align:middle line:10%
being a solar number-- and
there are many examples of that,

00:02:37.720 --> 00:02:40.930 align:middle line:10%
and these are some of the kinds
of things that I can actually

00:02:40.930 --> 00:02:44.670 align:middle line:10%
provide on my website, some
of the more detailed analysis

00:02:44.670 --> 00:02:49.760 align:middle line:10%
and examples of these
things for people to access

00:02:49.760 --> 00:02:53.730 align:middle line:10%
and how that shows up in
ancient traditions and so on.

00:02:53.730 --> 00:02:57.180 align:middle line:84%
But the idea, I think, is
that there could be times

00:02:57.180 --> 00:03:02.460 align:middle line:84%
when the sun's output
changes, for whatever reason,

00:03:02.460 --> 00:03:06.390 align:middle line:84%
and it, again, could have
considerable consequences

00:03:06.390 --> 00:03:10.050 align:middle line:84%
as far as life on the
surface of the Earth.

00:03:10.050 --> 00:03:14.610 align:middle line:10%
In Jay's book that he
wrote on the Hendaye stone,

00:03:14.610 --> 00:03:17.650 align:middle line:10%
there is an effigy
on one of the faces

00:03:17.650 --> 00:03:20.950 align:middle line:10%
of the stone of the solar
orb where it clearly

00:03:20.950 --> 00:03:25.820 align:middle line:10%
seems to signify that there are
two degrees of radiant output

00:03:25.820 --> 00:03:26.640 align:middle line:10%
to the sun.

00:03:26.640 --> 00:03:29.620 align:middle line:84%
And it very much recapitulates
some of the symbolism

00:03:29.620 --> 00:03:32.880 align:middle line:84%
that we've actually found like
that shows up into the Tarot

00:03:32.880 --> 00:03:36.330 align:middle line:84%
deck, this idea that
the sun may have

00:03:36.330 --> 00:03:39.910 align:middle line:90%
two types of radiant output.

00:03:39.910 --> 00:03:43.750 align:middle line:84%
And so I think that possibly
the negative connotation

00:03:43.750 --> 00:03:48.610 align:middle line:84%
could come from a tradition
or a knowledge of--

00:03:48.610 --> 00:03:50.420 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: A catastrophic
event at the hands

00:03:50.420 --> 00:03:51.420 align:middle line:90%
of the sun, so to speak.

00:03:51.420 --> 00:03:52.836 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: You've
got it, exactly.

00:03:52.836 --> 00:03:54.980 align:middle line:84%
Thank you for putting
those words in my mouth.

00:03:54.980 --> 00:03:56.370 align:middle line:90%
That's what I was trying to say.

00:03:56.370 --> 00:03:59.410 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: [LAUGHS] What the sun
giveth, the sun can taketh away

00:03:59.410 --> 00:04:00.271 align:middle line:90%
by way of life.

00:04:00.271 --> 00:04:02.020 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: And I
mentioned to you earlier,

00:04:02.020 --> 00:04:07.750 align:middle line:84%
I think maybe on the break, that
a culture, for example, living

00:04:07.750 --> 00:04:10.960 align:middle line:84%
in the Sahara Desert is going
to have a different relationship

00:04:10.960 --> 00:04:15.450 align:middle line:84%
with the sun, say, than
the Scandinavians living

00:04:15.450 --> 00:04:17.390 align:middle line:84%
at 60 degrees north
latitude where

00:04:17.390 --> 00:04:20.959 align:middle line:84%
the sun shows two or three
months out of the year.

00:04:20.959 --> 00:04:25.920 align:middle line:84%
And so I think that
that's possibly

00:04:25.920 --> 00:04:28.630 align:middle line:84%
what is being implicated
here, is this idea

00:04:28.630 --> 00:04:32.190 align:middle line:84%
that the number 666,
number one, it's

00:04:32.190 --> 00:04:34.930 align:middle line:84%
always associated with
the sun, archangels

00:04:34.930 --> 00:04:40.990 align:middle line:84%
of the sun, many
different gods associated

00:04:40.990 --> 00:04:43.230 align:middle line:84%
with the sun, Abraxas
and Mithras and so on.

00:04:43.230 --> 00:04:47.210 align:middle line:90%


00:04:47.210 --> 00:04:50.980 align:middle line:84%
But actually, in the
biblical verse itself,

00:04:50.980 --> 00:04:55.350 align:middle line:84%
it doesn't really necessarily
imply a negative connotation.

00:04:55.350 --> 00:04:56.740 align:middle line:84%
The biblical verse
reads, here is

00:04:56.740 --> 00:04:59.726 align:middle line:84%
wisdom; let him who
hath understanding count

00:04:59.726 --> 00:05:01.600 align:middle line:84%
the number of the beast,
for it in the number

00:05:01.600 --> 00:05:04.260 align:middle line:90%
of man, 600 threescore and six.

00:05:04.260 --> 00:05:09.630 align:middle line:84%
Now, the assumption is in the
more fundamentalist models

00:05:09.630 --> 00:05:12.270 align:middle line:84%
they're extracted from
the biblical writings.

00:05:12.270 --> 00:05:16.730 align:middle line:84%
There's a conflation of the
beast, the Antichrist, Lucifer,

00:05:16.730 --> 00:05:17.880 align:middle line:90%
the devil.

00:05:17.880 --> 00:05:21.820 align:middle line:84%
I think these are all
distinct concepts.

00:05:21.820 --> 00:05:25.560 align:middle line:84%
And we can't just
necessarily interchange them.

00:05:25.560 --> 00:05:30.420 align:middle line:84%
The beast is not necessarily
the same as diablo, the devil.

00:05:30.420 --> 00:05:34.350 align:middle line:84%
It's not necessarily the same
as Lucifer, the quote unquote,

00:05:34.350 --> 00:05:37.060 align:middle line:84%
which literally translates
as "bringer of light."

00:05:37.060 --> 00:05:38.390 align:middle line:90%
And that always puzzled me.

00:05:38.390 --> 00:05:41.540 align:middle line:84%
And we can come back to
that as we proceed here

00:05:41.540 --> 00:05:42.897 align:middle line:90%
when we start talking about--

00:05:42.897 --> 00:05:44.980 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well, we've
delved into the Urantia work

00:05:44.980 --> 00:05:47.750 align:middle line:84%
quite a bit in a
few interviews also

00:05:47.750 --> 00:05:49.450 align:middle line:84%
that talks about the
nature of Lucifer

00:05:49.450 --> 00:05:51.780 align:middle line:84%
and the Luciferian
rebellion and what

00:05:51.780 --> 00:05:54.410 align:middle line:84%
happened in those early
times as well, yeah.

00:05:54.410 --> 00:05:56.620 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: And that's
something I've never really

00:05:56.620 --> 00:05:58.870 align:middle line:84%
had the time to access
is the Urantia works.

00:05:58.870 --> 00:06:00.087 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: You're busy.

00:06:00.087 --> 00:06:02.170 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: There's a lot
of information out there.

00:06:02.170 --> 00:06:03.200 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: It's a
big book. [LAUGHS]

00:06:03.200 --> 00:06:03.866 align:middle line:90%
>>CARLSON: Yeah.

00:06:03.866 --> 00:06:07.090 align:middle line:84%
My focus has been on
I'm trying to bridge

00:06:07.090 --> 00:06:11.070 align:middle line:84%
the archaic traditions with
modern scientific findings.

00:06:11.070 --> 00:06:12.640 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yes, well,
let's talk about

00:06:12.640 --> 00:06:15.006 align:middle line:84%
modern scientific
findings and solar flares.

00:06:15.006 --> 00:06:16.630 align:middle line:84%
What are some of the
common things that

00:06:16.630 --> 00:06:18.570 align:middle line:84%
occur that we know of
that they've already

00:06:18.570 --> 00:06:22.710 align:middle line:84%
been able to chronicle when it
comes to sizable solar flares.

00:06:22.710 --> 00:06:24.440 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: Oh, yeah,
I mean obviously

00:06:24.440 --> 00:06:26.825 align:middle line:90%
our technologies are vulnerable.

00:06:26.825 --> 00:06:27.700 align:middle line:90%
And that's a concern.

00:06:27.700 --> 00:06:29.870 align:middle line:84%
And up to this point,
we've been lucky.

00:06:29.870 --> 00:06:32.090 align:middle line:84%
The intensity of these
events hasn't been such

00:06:32.090 --> 00:06:37.050 align:middle line:84%
that it's caused any kind
of a serious economic effect

00:06:37.050 --> 00:06:39.415 align:middle line:90%
or technological breakdown.

00:06:39.415 --> 00:06:41.770 align:middle line:84%
And this is not my
field of expertise,

00:06:41.770 --> 00:06:46.040 align:middle line:84%
but certainly for that,
I think Jay and people

00:06:46.040 --> 00:06:48.760 align:middle line:84%
like Robert Schoch who've
really gone into this

00:06:48.760 --> 00:06:52.590 align:middle line:84%
have made a pretty strong case
that that's one of the factors.

00:06:52.590 --> 00:06:54.190 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Everybody
pretty much knows

00:06:54.190 --> 00:06:57.260 align:middle line:84%
about the notion of solar
flares and having some outages

00:06:57.260 --> 00:06:58.249 align:middle line:90%
in computer systems.

00:06:58.249 --> 00:06:58.790 align:middle line:90%
We know that.

00:06:58.790 --> 00:07:01.260 align:middle line:84%
That's subtle technology
that's working

00:07:01.260 --> 00:07:02.600 align:middle line:90%
with electrical impulses.

00:07:02.600 --> 00:07:05.814 align:middle line:84%
So we get it's having an effect
on those electrical systems.

00:07:05.814 --> 00:07:07.480 align:middle line:84%
So what's it doing
to our bodies, right?

00:07:07.480 --> 00:07:09.799 align:middle line:84%
It's having an effect on
our electromagnetic system--

00:07:09.799 --> 00:07:10.840 align:middle line:90%
>>CARLSON: Good question.

00:07:10.840 --> 00:07:12.970 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: --and the
planet and all life forms.

00:07:12.970 --> 00:07:15.210 align:middle line:84%
So you can see how--
I can understand

00:07:15.210 --> 00:07:17.670 align:middle line:84%
how the sun and
that connotation,

00:07:17.670 --> 00:07:20.020 align:middle line:84%
if you have a
sizable enough blast,

00:07:20.020 --> 00:07:22.760 align:middle line:84%
would not be considered a
positive event on the planet.

00:07:22.760 --> 00:07:24.460 align:middle line:10%
>>CARLSON: Yeah,
in mythology, we

00:07:24.460 --> 00:07:28.880 align:middle line:10%
see a lot of this where what
is normally a benevolent god

00:07:28.880 --> 00:07:32.450 align:middle line:10%
or goddess, like Hathor in
Egypt, Egyptian tradition,

00:07:32.450 --> 00:07:35.970 align:middle line:10%
was normally a very
benevolent, nurturing goddess,

00:07:35.970 --> 00:07:38.640 align:middle line:10%
but on occasion
she could lose it.

00:07:38.640 --> 00:07:41.830 align:middle line:84%
And then she would
transform into Sekhmet.

00:07:41.830 --> 00:07:44.420 align:middle line:10%
And you didn't want
to deal with Sekhmet.

00:07:44.420 --> 00:07:47.300 align:middle line:10%
Sekhmet was the
lion-headed goddess

00:07:47.300 --> 00:07:49.970 align:middle line:10%
who actually, at
the command of Ra,

00:07:49.970 --> 00:07:52.850 align:middle line:10%
went down and basically
slayed mankind.

00:07:52.850 --> 00:07:56.280 align:middle line:84%
In the Egyptian version of
the destruction of the world,

00:07:56.280 --> 00:07:57.130 align:middle line:90%
that was Sekhmet.

00:07:57.130 --> 00:08:02.710 align:middle line:84%
But Sekhmet was the destructive
counterpart to Hathor,

00:08:02.710 --> 00:08:04.005 align:middle line:90%
who is normally, like I said--

00:08:04.005 --> 00:08:04.880 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Benevolent.

00:08:04.880 --> 00:08:05.860 align:middle line:90%
>>CARLSON: Right.

00:08:05.860 --> 00:08:08.040 align:middle line:90%
There's an old English proverb.

00:08:08.040 --> 00:08:08.540 align:middle line:90%
Let's see.

00:08:08.540 --> 00:08:10.490 align:middle line:90%
How does it go, again?

00:08:10.490 --> 00:08:14.300 align:middle line:84%
It's the idea that we
can't live without heat.

00:08:14.300 --> 00:08:15.630 align:middle line:90%
We can't live without the sun.

00:08:15.630 --> 00:08:17.700 align:middle line:90%
We can't live without water.

00:08:17.700 --> 00:08:21.850 align:middle line:84%
But in some cases, water
can be totally destructive.

00:08:21.850 --> 00:08:23.600 align:middle line:84%
And we'll be talking
about that as we

00:08:23.600 --> 00:08:27.385 align:middle line:84%
get on here and the stories
of the great deluge.

00:08:27.385 --> 00:08:30.340 align:middle line:84%
And when you've used
the term antedeluvian,

00:08:30.340 --> 00:08:32.240 align:middle line:90%
that means pre-flood.

00:08:32.240 --> 00:08:35.020 align:middle line:84%
And we've always
assumed to the extent

00:08:35.020 --> 00:08:38.179 align:middle line:84%
that rational science
has even acknowledged

00:08:38.179 --> 00:08:42.950 align:middle line:84%
the fact that there is this
widespread, universal tradition

00:08:42.950 --> 00:08:43.489 align:middle line:90%
of--

00:08:43.489 --> 00:08:45.312 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: In all
ancient religions.

00:08:45.312 --> 00:08:46.770 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: Yes,
all over the world,

00:08:46.770 --> 00:08:51.740 align:middle line:84%
this myth about the destruction
of the world by water.

00:08:51.740 --> 00:08:54.670 align:middle line:84%
Not quite as well known,
but also very prevalent

00:08:54.670 --> 00:08:57.500 align:middle line:84%
are myths about the destruction
of the world by fire.

00:08:57.500 --> 00:08:59.590 align:middle line:84%
And if you look at the
Bible, interestingly, it's

00:08:59.590 --> 00:09:01.010 align:middle line:90%
kind of bookending.

00:09:01.010 --> 00:09:05.850 align:middle line:84%
At the front end in Genesis, we
have Noah and the destruction

00:09:05.850 --> 00:09:07.230 align:middle line:90%
of the world by water.

00:09:07.230 --> 00:09:10.500 align:middle line:84%
And then in the apocalyptic
visions at the end of the book,

00:09:10.500 --> 00:09:12.480 align:middle line:84%
it's the destruction
of the world by fire.

00:09:12.480 --> 00:09:14.021 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And hellfire
and damnation.

00:09:14.021 --> 00:09:15.900 align:middle line:90%
>>CARLSON: Exactly, exactly.

00:09:15.900 --> 00:09:19.710 align:middle line:84%
Now, we can take those
and dismiss them out

00:09:19.710 --> 00:09:23.670 align:middle line:84%
of hand as just being
the superstitious ravings

00:09:23.670 --> 00:09:29.180 align:middle line:84%
or imaginations of a
pre-scientific, barbaric mind,

00:09:29.180 --> 00:09:32.790 align:middle line:84%
or we can acknowledge
that maybe, perhaps,

00:09:32.790 --> 00:09:37.310 align:middle line:84%
those traditions
reflect real events,

00:09:37.310 --> 00:09:39.770 align:middle line:84%
that there's a reality
behind those myths.

00:09:39.770 --> 00:09:44.900 align:middle line:84%
And as a geomythologist
or an astromythologist,

00:09:44.900 --> 00:09:48.450 align:middle line:84%
that is one of the
tenets of these emerging

00:09:48.450 --> 00:09:50.870 align:middle line:84%
disciplines of geomythology
and astromythology,

00:09:50.870 --> 00:09:54.230 align:middle line:84%
is that behind these
myths, there are realities

00:09:54.230 --> 00:09:57.610 align:middle line:84%
and that those myths can lead
us into a deeper understanding

00:09:57.610 --> 00:09:59.090 align:middle line:90%
of what those realities are.

00:09:59.090 --> 00:10:01.548 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I think some of the
work-- I recently interviewed

00:10:01.548 --> 00:10:04.080 align:middle line:84%
David Talbot, who of course
is associated with Walter

00:10:04.080 --> 00:10:06.270 align:middle line:84%
Thornhill, and I think
a lot of their work

00:10:06.270 --> 00:10:07.970 align:middle line:90%
is demonstrating exactly that.

00:10:07.970 --> 00:10:11.020 align:middle line:84%
And they're even able to look
under electron microscopes

00:10:11.020 --> 00:10:13.970 align:middle line:84%
at the actual physical
phenomena that

00:10:13.970 --> 00:10:17.430 align:middle line:84%
created those ancient symbols
and what that meant on a larger

00:10:17.430 --> 00:10:19.440 align:middle line:90%
cosmological level.

00:10:19.440 --> 00:10:21.490 align:middle line:90%
So it is coming together.

00:10:21.490 --> 00:10:24.400 align:middle line:84%
It is coming together that
these weren't just stories.

00:10:24.400 --> 00:10:26.430 align:middle line:84%
And how do you
have one story that

00:10:26.430 --> 00:10:28.940 align:middle line:84%
persists throughout history
and across the globe?

00:10:28.940 --> 00:10:32.400 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: Right,
well, one way around

00:10:32.400 --> 00:10:35.330 align:middle line:84%
that has always been to say,
well, if this or that tribe--

00:10:35.330 --> 00:10:37.127 align:middle line:90%
like American Indian tribes.

00:10:37.127 --> 00:10:38.710 align:middle line:84%
Well, they heard it
from missionaries.

00:10:38.710 --> 00:10:39.960 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah, right.

00:10:39.960 --> 00:10:43.630 align:middle line:10%
>>CARLSON: But look at like
for example George Catlin,

00:10:43.630 --> 00:10:46.440 align:middle line:10%
the famous Indian artist
who spent decades--

00:10:46.440 --> 00:10:51.760 align:middle line:10%
he wrote his book "Last Rambles
Amongst the American Indians."

00:10:51.760 --> 00:10:56.930 align:middle line:84%
He spent decades roaming around,
and he visited over 120 tribes

00:10:56.930 --> 00:10:59.510 align:middle line:84%
throughout North
and Central America.

00:10:59.510 --> 00:11:03.370 align:middle line:84%
And at the epilogue
of his book, that

00:11:03.370 --> 00:11:05.130 align:middle line:84%
amongst all of
these tribes, they

00:11:05.130 --> 00:11:09.610 align:middle line:84%
have many different traditions,
they many languages,

00:11:09.610 --> 00:11:14.660 align:middle line:84%
unique and different customs,
but what they all had in common

00:11:14.660 --> 00:11:21.260 align:middle line:84%
was a memory of a great deluge
and that their tribe, whichever

00:11:21.260 --> 00:11:27.610 align:middle line:84%
tribe, was descended from the
survivors of this great deluge.

00:11:27.610 --> 00:11:30.300 align:middle line:84%
Now, a big part of what I've
been doing over the last 20

00:11:30.300 --> 00:11:35.260 align:middle line:84%
years is travelling over North
America documenting the hard

00:11:35.260 --> 00:11:39.700 align:middle line:84%
physical evidence that yes,
there really was gigantic,

00:11:39.700 --> 00:11:43.690 align:middle line:84%
inconceivably huge floods
that swept over this continent

00:11:43.690 --> 00:11:45.160 align:middle line:90%
at the end of the last ice age.

00:11:45.160 --> 00:11:47.540 align:middle line:84%
And it's those
events that I think

00:11:47.540 --> 00:11:51.580 align:middle line:84%
are being preserved in these
Native American traditions.

00:11:51.580 --> 00:11:53.990 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yes, OK, so
let's talk about when

00:11:53.990 --> 00:11:57.820 align:middle line:84%
we're looking at cosmic patterns
and cycles of catastrophe.

00:11:57.820 --> 00:12:00.440 align:middle line:84%
That's the one that's
most commonly pointed to.

00:12:00.440 --> 00:12:03.000 align:middle line:84%
Now, we're looking
at generally now

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:07.220 align:middle line:84%
it seems people are looking at
around 13,000 years ago, right?

00:12:07.220 --> 00:12:09.080 align:middle line:90%
Half of a precessional cycle.

00:12:09.080 --> 00:12:11.870 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: Exactly, half
of a precessional cycle.

00:12:11.870 --> 00:12:18.090 align:middle line:84%
In the last show, we talked
about the number 25,920.

00:12:18.090 --> 00:12:20.110 align:middle line:84%
If you could take that
and cut that in half,

00:12:20.110 --> 00:12:22.810 align:middle line:90%
it's 12,960, which is--

00:12:22.810 --> 00:12:25.660 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Which is rounding
it out to 26 and 13.

00:12:25.660 --> 00:12:27.690 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: 26 and
13, yeah, but just

00:12:27.690 --> 00:12:32.110 align:middle line:84%
to tie it back to those sacred
numbers we were talking about.

00:12:32.110 --> 00:12:35.800 align:middle line:84%
25, 30 years ago, as
I was immersing myself

00:12:35.800 --> 00:12:38.990 align:middle line:84%
into the studies of
these archaic traditions

00:12:38.990 --> 00:12:42.750 align:middle line:84%
about patterns and cycles
and so forth, those numbers

00:12:42.750 --> 00:12:45.880 align:middle line:84%
kept coming up over
and over again, right?

00:12:45.880 --> 00:12:48.580 align:middle line:84%
It was clear to me
that they sure seemed

00:12:48.580 --> 00:12:50.940 align:middle line:84%
to be pointing to
something happening,

00:12:50.940 --> 00:12:52.830 align:middle line:90%
say, 13,000 years ago.

00:12:52.830 --> 00:12:55.360 align:middle line:84%
Now, while I'm doing
this, and actually I

00:12:55.360 --> 00:12:59.420 align:middle line:84%
gave a series of lectures at
Warren Wilson College in 1996,

00:12:59.420 --> 00:13:01.890 align:middle line:84%
where I was pointing
out that as a date,

00:13:01.890 --> 00:13:06.440 align:middle line:84%
that something extraordinary
happened, right?

00:13:06.440 --> 00:13:09.740 align:middle line:84%
And I at that point had not read
Graham Hancock's "Fingerprints

00:13:09.740 --> 00:13:10.720 align:middle line:90%
of the Gods" yet.

00:13:10.720 --> 00:13:13.880 align:middle line:84%
Unbeknownst to me, he
had just published a book

00:13:13.880 --> 00:13:16.020 align:middle line:84%
where he amasses
all of this evidence

00:13:16.020 --> 00:13:18.140 align:middle line:84%
and concludes that
all of this stuff

00:13:18.140 --> 00:13:20.400 align:middle line:84%
seems to be pointing
to something

00:13:20.400 --> 00:13:22.960 align:middle line:90%
at that epoch occurring, right?

00:13:22.960 --> 00:13:27.630 align:middle line:84%
So independently, we had
come to this same conclusion.

00:13:27.630 --> 00:13:29.810 align:middle line:84%
And I had come to it
mainly from looking

00:13:29.810 --> 00:13:33.690 align:middle line:84%
at ancient symbolism and
these ancient patterns

00:13:33.690 --> 00:13:36.370 align:middle line:84%
and the numbers that were
associated with them.

00:13:36.370 --> 00:13:40.770 align:middle line:84%
And when I traveled
over Europe in 1989,

00:13:40.770 --> 00:13:42.420 align:middle line:84%
one of the things
that I did was I

00:13:42.420 --> 00:13:43.810 align:middle line:90%
went to a lot of the cathedrals.

00:13:43.810 --> 00:13:45.518 align:middle line:84%
I was mainly looking
at the architecture.

00:13:45.518 --> 00:13:48.450 align:middle line:10%
But what really struck
me in the symbolism

00:13:48.450 --> 00:13:50.580 align:middle line:10%
particularly--
Chartres Cathedral

00:13:50.580 --> 00:13:52.690 align:middle line:10%
is a beautiful example, OK?

00:13:52.690 --> 00:13:56.540 align:middle line:10%
When you walk up to the Western
facade of Chartres Cathedral

00:13:56.540 --> 00:13:58.680 align:middle line:10%
at the Portal of
Judgment, as it's called,

00:13:58.680 --> 00:14:01.480 align:middle line:10%
and that's a reference
to judgment day, what

00:14:01.480 --> 00:14:06.560 align:middle line:10%
we see there is the effigy
of Christ, Christ in majesty,

00:14:06.560 --> 00:14:10.240 align:middle line:10%
seated within the
vesica, which is

00:14:10.240 --> 00:14:12.440 align:middle line:10%
the preeminent feminine symbol.

00:14:12.440 --> 00:14:15.850 align:middle line:84%
It's also the symbol
that represents

00:14:15.850 --> 00:14:20.320 align:middle line:84%
the inauguration of the
whole of sacred geometry.

00:14:20.320 --> 00:14:22.920 align:middle line:84%
Because through the
overlapping of two circles

00:14:22.920 --> 00:14:25.260 align:middle line:84%
of equal diameter such that
the circumference of one

00:14:25.260 --> 00:14:26.720 align:middle line:84%
falls on the center
of the other,

00:14:26.720 --> 00:14:28.930 align:middle line:84%
you get this-- a
mathematician would think it

00:14:28.930 --> 00:14:31.330 align:middle line:84%
as a Venn diagram,
this overlap, which

00:14:31.330 --> 00:14:35.820 align:middle line:84%
is this lozenge-shaped
almost boat-shaped figure.

00:14:35.820 --> 00:14:40.050 align:middle line:84%
And out of that emerges the
whole edifice of geometry,

00:14:40.050 --> 00:14:42.620 align:middle line:84%
the whole edifice of Euclidean
geometry, all of the forms

00:14:42.620 --> 00:14:44.630 align:middle line:90%
and patterns emerge from that.

00:14:44.630 --> 00:14:46.530 align:middle line:84%
So in a sense, it
is like a womb.

00:14:46.530 --> 00:14:51.350 align:middle line:84%
But it was also imagined as
a gateway between worlds,

00:14:51.350 --> 00:14:53.120 align:middle line:90%
between domains.

00:14:53.120 --> 00:14:55.610 align:middle line:84%
And in the case of
Chartres Cathedral

00:14:55.610 --> 00:14:59.850 align:middle line:84%
and many of the others, you see
the master sits in that vesica

00:14:59.850 --> 00:15:02.160 align:middle line:90%
as if he's the gatekeeper.

00:15:02.160 --> 00:15:06.080 align:middle line:84%
And he is usually pictured
with a book in hand.

00:15:06.080 --> 00:15:08.350 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes the book
is shown open.

00:15:08.350 --> 00:15:10.010 align:middle line:90%
Sometimes it's closed.

00:15:10.010 --> 00:15:14.920 align:middle line:84%
If it's open, that's indicating
within that symbolical edifice,

00:15:14.920 --> 00:15:19.990 align:middle line:84%
there is a teaching that is now
being divulged unto the world.

00:15:19.990 --> 00:15:20.890 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:15:20.890 --> 00:15:24.080 align:middle line:84%
The esoteric is
becoming exoteric.

00:15:24.080 --> 00:15:28.310 align:middle line:84%
If the book is closed, it's
indicating to the initiate

00:15:28.310 --> 00:15:31.830 align:middle line:84%
that there's a secret there,
a secret that's not yet

00:15:31.830 --> 00:15:34.340 align:middle line:84%
ready to be revealed
to the world.

00:15:34.340 --> 00:15:36.130 align:middle line:90%
And you'll see it both ways.

00:15:36.130 --> 00:15:38.330 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And these
gatekeepers are often

00:15:38.330 --> 00:15:42.680 align:middle line:84%
known to us as prominent figures
in our religious history,

00:15:42.680 --> 00:15:46.660 align:middle line:84%
as beings who came along to
impart a certain knowledge

00:15:46.660 --> 00:15:47.720 align:middle line:90%
at a given time.

00:15:47.720 --> 00:15:50.160 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: There are
effigies of Buddha

00:15:50.160 --> 00:15:53.580 align:middle line:90%
seated within the same vesica.

00:15:53.580 --> 00:15:56.030 align:middle line:84%
And vesica comes from
the same as the word

00:15:56.030 --> 00:16:00.830 align:middle line:84%
vessel, which means like a
container that carries us

00:16:00.830 --> 00:16:03.540 align:middle line:90%
from one domain to another, OK?

00:16:03.540 --> 00:16:06.700 align:middle line:84%
So in Chartres
Cathedral, you've got

00:16:06.700 --> 00:16:08.935 align:middle line:84%
Christ in majesty seated
within the vesica.

00:16:08.935 --> 00:16:10.890 align:middle line:84%
It's referred to
as the mandoral.

00:16:10.890 --> 00:16:13.630 align:middle line:84%
It's up in the tympanum
above the doorway.

00:16:13.630 --> 00:16:16.830 align:middle line:84%
Surrounding are the four
beasts of the apocalypse,

00:16:16.830 --> 00:16:19.570 align:middle line:84%
which are also the four
evangelists, Matthew, Mark,

00:16:19.570 --> 00:16:22.260 align:middle line:84%
Luke, and John, in
the exoteric sense.

00:16:22.260 --> 00:16:26.090 align:middle line:84%
In the esoteric sense, it
represents the four seasons

00:16:26.090 --> 00:16:28.590 align:middle line:90%
of the great year, right?

00:16:28.590 --> 00:16:30.160 align:middle line:90%
The bull is obviously Taurus.

00:16:30.160 --> 00:16:32.630 align:middle line:90%
The lion is obviously Leo.

00:16:32.630 --> 00:16:35.200 align:middle line:90%
The angel is Aquarius.

00:16:35.200 --> 00:16:40.180 align:middle line:84%
And the eagle is Aquila,
the constellation the ego

00:16:40.180 --> 00:16:43.200 align:middle line:84%
that rises with the
scorpion and is often

00:16:43.200 --> 00:16:47.290 align:middle line:84%
considered to be the celestial
counterpart of Scorpio,

00:16:47.290 --> 00:16:51.140 align:middle line:84%
of which Scorpio is the
terrestrial counterpart,

00:16:51.140 --> 00:16:53.910 align:middle line:84%
the positive and the
negative polarity of it.

00:16:53.910 --> 00:16:57.610 align:middle line:84%
But it represents, as a
symbol of time, the eagle

00:16:57.610 --> 00:17:00.220 align:middle line:84%
represents that same
moment, that same time

00:17:00.220 --> 00:17:02.270 align:middle line:90%
during the course of the year.

00:17:02.270 --> 00:17:05.119 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Roughly a 5,500-year
portion of the cycle.

00:17:05.119 --> 00:17:08.619 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: Well, actually
if you take the 25,920

00:17:08.619 --> 00:17:11.420 align:middle line:84%
and think of it as the four
seasons of the great year,

00:17:11.420 --> 00:17:17.740 align:middle line:84%
and each of those signs, Taurus,
Leo, Aquarius, and Scorpio,

00:17:17.740 --> 00:17:19.390 align:middle line:90%
they are the fixed signs.

00:17:19.390 --> 00:17:21.800 align:middle line:84%
And each of the
fixed signs is taken

00:17:21.800 --> 00:17:25.930 align:middle line:84%
to represent its seasonal
counterpart, right?

00:17:25.930 --> 00:17:30.410 align:middle line:84%
So Taurus is a symbol that
represents spring, right?

00:17:30.410 --> 00:17:33.670 align:middle line:84%
Leo represents summer
and so on, but likewise

00:17:33.670 --> 00:17:34.640 align:middle line:90%
within the great year.

00:17:34.640 --> 00:17:36.550 align:middle line:84%
So in the great
year model, there

00:17:36.550 --> 00:17:40.490 align:middle line:84%
is 12 months of the year,
symbolized by the 12 signs.

00:17:40.490 --> 00:17:42.620 align:middle line:84%
And there are four
seasons, symbolized

00:17:42.620 --> 00:17:45.580 align:middle line:84%
by the bull, the lion,
the eagle, and the angel,

00:17:45.580 --> 00:17:48.750 align:middle line:84%
or in some cases a
humanoid figure, right?

00:17:48.750 --> 00:17:55.150 align:middle line:84%
Well, if you divide the 25,920
to get the four seasons,

00:17:55.150 --> 00:17:58.600 align:middle line:84%
each comprised of three months,
or you multiply the three

00:17:58.600 --> 00:18:01.380 align:middle line:84%
months, which are
each 2,160, you

00:18:01.380 --> 00:18:05.570 align:middle line:90%
get 6,480 years for each one.

00:18:05.570 --> 00:18:08.050 align:middle line:84%
Now that's interesting, because
in our previous discussion,

00:18:08.050 --> 00:18:10.950 align:middle line:84%
we were talking about
the platonic solids.

00:18:10.950 --> 00:18:13.950 align:middle line:10%
The degree measure
of the dodecahedron,

00:18:13.950 --> 00:18:18.180 align:middle line:10%
which Plato conceived of as a
model of the universe, there

00:18:18.180 --> 00:18:20.960 align:middle line:10%
are 12 pentagonal faces.

00:18:20.960 --> 00:18:26.050 align:middle line:84%
Each of those faces, the sides
intersect at 108 degrees.

00:18:26.050 --> 00:18:29.480 align:middle line:10%
There are five vertices,
so it's 540 per face times

00:18:29.480 --> 00:18:35.190 align:middle line:10%
12 gives you 6,480 degrees,
measures the dodecahedron,

00:18:35.190 --> 00:18:39.701 align:middle line:10%
and 6,480 years measures
the duration of one season

00:18:39.701 --> 00:18:40.450 align:middle line:10%
of the great year.

00:18:40.450 --> 00:18:41.630 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: A quarter
of the great year.

00:18:41.630 --> 00:18:43.463 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: A quarter
of the great year, yes.

00:18:43.463 --> 00:18:45.000 align:middle line:84%
Now, what I have
been doing is going

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:49.820 align:middle line:84%
through hundreds and hundreds
of scientific articles,

00:18:49.820 --> 00:18:53.870 align:middle line:84%
going back 50 years, more
than that, going back really

00:18:53.870 --> 00:18:56.840 align:middle line:84%
even to the turn of the century
but accelerating as we get up

00:18:56.840 --> 00:19:00.870 align:middle line:84%
to the '70s and the '80s,
'90s as dating becomes better,

00:19:00.870 --> 00:19:05.840 align:middle line:84%
and looking at the events that I
think of as the discontinuities

00:19:05.840 --> 00:19:09.480 align:middle line:84%
within the uniform
change, the event nodes,

00:19:09.480 --> 00:19:12.100 align:middle line:90%
and plotting those.

00:19:12.100 --> 00:19:14.850 align:middle line:84%
And what we see
happening or what

00:19:14.850 --> 00:19:17.980 align:middle line:84%
I have seen happening in
that is that they cluster.

00:19:17.980 --> 00:19:21.560 align:middle line:84%
Now, I suspect that as
we refine our dating,

00:19:21.560 --> 00:19:23.530 align:middle line:84%
that clustering is
going to tighten up.

00:19:23.530 --> 00:19:25.320 align:middle line:84%
And what we're going
to see is that there

00:19:25.320 --> 00:19:31.320 align:middle line:84%
was major global change at
13,000 years ago, right?

00:19:31.320 --> 00:19:34.640 align:middle line:84%
And there was also
major-- not as profound,

00:19:34.640 --> 00:19:38.880 align:middle line:84%
but there was major global
change around 6,500 years ago.

00:19:38.880 --> 00:19:41.250 align:middle line:84%
If we go back to
the age of Scorpio,

00:19:41.250 --> 00:19:43.750 align:middle line:84%
for example, what we
find is that is what's

00:19:43.750 --> 00:19:50.320 align:middle line:84%
considered what they call the
LGM, the Late Glacial Maximum.

00:19:50.320 --> 00:19:52.760 align:middle line:84%
And it was during that
Age of Scorpio-- now,

00:19:52.760 --> 00:19:55.050 align:middle line:84%
the scientists, of course,
don't use that terminology,

00:19:55.050 --> 00:19:57.810 align:middle line:84%
but within the astronomical
or astrological sense,

00:19:57.810 --> 00:20:00.950 align:middle line:84%
the Age of Scorpio would
be that period roughly

00:20:00.950 --> 00:20:03.400 align:middle line:90%
bracketing 18,000 years ago.

00:20:03.400 --> 00:20:06.190 align:middle line:84%
And during that
time, the planet went

00:20:06.190 --> 00:20:10.570 align:middle line:84%
into this extreme deep
freeze, extremely cold,

00:20:10.570 --> 00:20:12.560 align:middle line:90%
I mean, just bitterly cold.

00:20:12.560 --> 00:20:15.420 align:middle line:84%
And the glaciers
worldwide expanded

00:20:15.420 --> 00:20:16.550 align:middle line:90%
to this enormous extent.

00:20:16.550 --> 00:20:19.930 align:middle line:90%


00:20:19.930 --> 00:20:25.370 align:middle line:84%
Roughly 6,000 years later,
come about 13,000 years,

00:20:25.370 --> 00:20:27.530 align:middle line:84%
what we find happening
is that there's

00:20:27.530 --> 00:20:33.620 align:middle line:84%
a succession of extreme warming
spasms, which up to this

00:20:33.620 --> 00:20:38.060 align:middle line:84%
point the cause of
which is unidentified.

00:20:38.060 --> 00:20:40.090 align:middle line:90%
But it's clearly happened.

00:20:40.090 --> 00:20:45.070 align:middle line:84%
And this can be documented by
multiple lines of evidence.

00:20:45.070 --> 00:20:46.700 align:middle line:84%
Marine geologists
and oceanographers

00:20:46.700 --> 00:20:49.650 align:middle line:84%
have looked at the
rise of sea level

00:20:49.650 --> 00:20:52.350 align:middle line:84%
at the end of the last
ice age and realized

00:20:52.350 --> 00:20:55.260 align:middle line:84%
that unlike what we thought
40, 50 years ago, that

00:20:55.260 --> 00:20:58.300 align:middle line:84%
would have been a nice smooth
rise over tens of thousands

00:20:58.300 --> 00:21:02.660 align:middle line:84%
of years, there were these
abrupt episodes of what

00:21:02.660 --> 00:21:07.419 align:middle line:84%
they call CREs,
Catastrophic Rise Events.

00:21:07.419 --> 00:21:08.835 align:middle line:84%
And there were two
major ones that

00:21:08.835 --> 00:21:11.168 align:middle line:84%
have now been identified that
are called meltwater pulse

00:21:11.168 --> 00:21:14.380 align:middle line:90%
1a, meltwater pulse 1b.

00:21:14.380 --> 00:21:17.360 align:middle line:84%
And what we see is that
superimposed upon what we would

00:21:17.360 --> 00:21:19.135 align:middle line:84%
think of as the
smooth curve, there

00:21:19.135 --> 00:21:22.620 align:middle line:84%
are these two huge
spikes of meltwater.

00:21:22.620 --> 00:21:27.760 align:middle line:84%
Now, in order to convert
glacial ice into meltwater

00:21:27.760 --> 00:21:29.700 align:middle line:90%
takes energy.

00:21:29.700 --> 00:21:32.830 align:middle line:84%
In the early '70s,
a team of scientists

00:21:32.830 --> 00:21:34.220 align:middle line:90%
held at a conference.

00:21:34.220 --> 00:21:37.270 align:middle line:90%
I think it was in 1972 or '73.

00:21:37.270 --> 00:21:38.700 align:middle line:84%
Some of the leading
glaciologists

00:21:38.700 --> 00:21:42.308 align:middle line:84%
and climatologists of the
day held this conference.

00:21:42.308 --> 00:21:43.180 align:middle line:90%


00:21:43.180 --> 00:21:48.770 align:middle line:84%
Now, radiocarbon dating was
invented in the early '50s

00:21:48.770 --> 00:21:51.940 align:middle line:90%
by Walter Libby.

00:21:51.940 --> 00:21:54.030 align:middle line:84%
20 years later,
they had accumulated

00:21:54.030 --> 00:21:56.480 align:middle line:84%
enough of these
radiocarbon dates

00:21:56.480 --> 00:21:58.280 align:middle line:84%
that they were now
being able to create

00:21:58.280 --> 00:22:01.670 align:middle line:90%
these models of climate change.

00:22:01.670 --> 00:22:05.040 align:middle line:84%
The previous idea of
this was that the ice age

00:22:05.040 --> 00:22:10.650 align:middle line:84%
had been this affair that
took 100,000 years to come on,

00:22:10.650 --> 00:22:15.560 align:middle line:90%
100,000 to disappear.

00:22:15.560 --> 00:22:18.450 align:middle line:84%
But now, they're suddenly
realizing it's only

00:22:18.450 --> 00:22:20.840 align:middle line:90%
a fraction of that time, see?

00:22:20.840 --> 00:22:24.270 align:middle line:84%
So what became
apparent by the early

00:22:24.270 --> 00:22:29.470 align:middle line:84%
'70s was that 18,000
years ago, from 18,000,

00:22:29.470 --> 00:22:31.200 align:middle line:84%
say, to 15,000
years ago, you had

00:22:31.200 --> 00:22:35.080 align:middle line:84%
somewhere around 6 million
cubic miles of glacial ice

00:22:35.080 --> 00:22:38.060 align:middle line:84%
piled up over North America,
Northwestern Europe.

00:22:38.060 --> 00:22:40.450 align:middle line:84%
Antarctica was probably
substantially bigger

00:22:40.450 --> 00:22:44.040 align:middle line:90%
than it is now.

00:22:44.040 --> 00:22:48.700 align:middle line:84%
And then 5,000 or 6,000
years later, it's gone.

00:22:48.700 --> 00:22:49.800 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: The ice is gone?

00:22:49.800 --> 00:22:50.100 align:middle line:90%
>>CARLSON: The ice is gone.

00:22:50.100 --> 00:22:52.080 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And then
that comes back

00:22:52.080 --> 00:22:53.590 align:middle line:90%
into Graham Hancock's work.

00:22:53.590 --> 00:22:56.835 align:middle line:84%
And now you have a vegetation
showing in Antarctica.

00:22:56.835 --> 00:22:57.460 align:middle line:90%
>>CARLSON: Yes.

00:22:57.460 --> 00:23:01.600 align:middle line:10%
And one of the thing that Graham
Hancock has been focusing us on

00:23:01.600 --> 00:23:03.920 align:middle line:10%
is what's called
the Younger Dryas.

00:23:03.920 --> 00:23:05.820 align:middle line:10%
Younger Dryas was
this spell that

00:23:05.820 --> 00:23:12.470 align:middle line:10%
lasted about 1,300 years from
about, say, 12,900 years ago

00:23:12.470 --> 00:23:15.770 align:middle line:10%
to about 11,600, right in there.

00:23:15.770 --> 00:23:18.950 align:middle line:84%
Now, here's the
scenario as it is now

00:23:18.950 --> 00:23:22.220 align:middle line:84%
coming based upon the
cutting-edge evidence,

00:23:22.220 --> 00:23:24.790 align:middle line:84%
is that between 18,000 and
15,000 years ago, you've

00:23:24.790 --> 00:23:28.480 align:middle line:84%
got this full-blown ice
age, over-- all of Canada

00:23:28.480 --> 00:23:32.850 align:middle line:84%
is buried under an ice sheet,
where major cities are now,

00:23:32.850 --> 00:23:37.260 align:middle line:84%
like New York, Boston,
Philadelphia, Chicago,

00:23:37.260 --> 00:23:40.560 align:middle line:84%
the Twin Cities,
Detroit, Seattle.

00:23:40.560 --> 00:23:44.250 align:middle line:84%
All of those, the ice is
thousands of feet thick.

00:23:44.250 --> 00:23:47.000 align:middle line:84%
And when people start
thinking in geological terms,

00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:49.300 align:middle line:84%
they think, OK,
millions of years

00:23:49.300 --> 00:23:53.030 align:middle line:84%
or whatever, we're
talking 13,000 years ago,

00:23:53.030 --> 00:23:55.646 align:middle line:84%
which is not long at all
in the geological sense.

00:23:55.646 --> 00:23:58.270 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So what happened over
that 1,300-year period of time?

00:23:58.270 --> 00:24:00.020 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: Well,
here's what happened.

00:24:00.020 --> 00:24:03.700 align:middle line:84%
Somewhere between 15,000
and 13,000 years ago,

00:24:03.700 --> 00:24:05.550 align:middle line:90%
the ice began to shrink.

00:24:05.550 --> 00:24:07.690 align:middle line:90%
And it began to disappear.

00:24:07.690 --> 00:24:11.240 align:middle line:90%
And sea levels started rising.

00:24:11.240 --> 00:24:14.730 align:middle line:84%
And during that 2,000
years, the pace of change

00:24:14.730 --> 00:24:18.120 align:middle line:84%
would have been sort of what
one would have expected based

00:24:18.120 --> 00:24:22.510 align:middle line:84%
upon our observations of modern
glacial recession in the wake

00:24:22.510 --> 00:24:27.780 align:middle line:84%
of the Little Ice Age, which
lasted from about 1,400 years

00:24:27.780 --> 00:24:30.442 align:middle line:90%
AD to about 1850 AD.

00:24:30.442 --> 00:24:32.900 align:middle line:84%
And we should come back to
that, because this is important.

00:24:32.900 --> 00:24:37.520 align:middle line:84%
The Little Ice Age was an
analog for the Great Ice Age.

00:24:37.520 --> 00:24:40.840 align:middle line:84%
And the Little Ice
Age was a period

00:24:40.840 --> 00:24:46.430 align:middle line:84%
that essentially the planet
cooled and was colder than it

00:24:46.430 --> 00:24:48.420 align:middle line:90%
had been in 10,000 years.

00:24:48.420 --> 00:24:50.850 align:middle line:84%
And the glaciers worldwide,
while they weren't anywhere

00:24:50.850 --> 00:24:53.190 align:middle line:84%
near what they were
during the Great Ice Age,

00:24:53.190 --> 00:24:55.280 align:middle line:84%
were bigger during
the Little Ice Age,

00:24:55.280 --> 00:24:57.840 align:middle line:84%
again, than they had
been in 10,000 years.

00:24:57.840 --> 00:25:01.150 align:middle line:84%
So it's important when we
look at modern climate change

00:25:01.150 --> 00:25:05.720 align:middle line:84%
to understand that our baseline
is the end of the Little Ice

00:25:05.720 --> 00:25:07.580 align:middle line:90%
Age, right?

00:25:07.580 --> 00:25:11.590 align:middle line:84%
Well, now from
that, what we see is

00:25:11.590 --> 00:25:14.550 align:middle line:84%
that the ice that
had grown-- there

00:25:14.550 --> 00:25:16.520 align:middle line:84%
were whole villages,
like in the Swiss Alps,

00:25:16.520 --> 00:25:18.500 align:middle line:84%
for example, that
got swallowed up

00:25:18.500 --> 00:25:20.900 align:middle line:84%
by the growth of the glaciers
during the Little Ice

00:25:20.900 --> 00:25:23.770 align:middle line:84%
Age, villages that
had to be abandoned.

00:25:23.770 --> 00:25:26.480 align:middle line:84%
And there's many
paintings and sketches

00:25:26.480 --> 00:25:30.970 align:middle line:84%
and artists' depictions from
the 1700s and 1800s showing

00:25:30.970 --> 00:25:33.560 align:middle line:84%
these massive glaciers
growing out of the mountains

00:25:33.560 --> 00:25:37.400 align:middle line:84%
down into the valleys and
overrunning farms and so on.

00:25:37.400 --> 00:25:43.530 align:middle line:84%
Well, with the end of the
Little Ice Age around 1820 1850,

00:25:43.530 --> 00:25:45.900 align:middle line:84%
these glaciers start
shrinking back.

00:25:45.900 --> 00:25:48.500 align:middle line:84%
Now, as a result of
the shrinking back,

00:25:48.500 --> 00:25:49.850 align:middle line:90%
many of the rivers got swollen.

00:25:49.850 --> 00:25:53.340 align:middle line:84%
There were proglacial lakes
that broke through and created

00:25:53.340 --> 00:25:55.690 align:middle line:84%
some pretty significant
floods, but not

00:25:55.690 --> 00:25:59.340 align:middle line:84%
anywhere remotely close to what
we saw at the end of the Great

00:25:59.340 --> 00:26:00.300 align:middle line:90%
Ice Age.

00:26:00.300 --> 00:26:04.400 align:middle line:84%
But the models of glacier
recession that were in place

00:26:04.400 --> 00:26:08.310 align:middle line:84%
were derived from what we had
seen from the Little Ice Age,

00:26:08.310 --> 00:26:09.990 align:middle line:90%
the glaciers shrinking back.

00:26:09.990 --> 00:26:13.030 align:middle line:90%
And so then here's what happens.

00:26:13.030 --> 00:26:15.160 align:middle line:84%
At 15,000 years ago,
the great ice sheets

00:26:15.160 --> 00:26:17.270 align:middle line:90%
start shrinking back.

00:26:17.270 --> 00:26:21.459 align:middle line:84%
At 13,000 years ago, something
interrupts that process.

00:26:21.459 --> 00:26:23.000 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Now, is
this something that

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:26.046 align:middle line:84%
is showing in the carbon dating
that you were talking about?

00:26:26.046 --> 00:26:26.670 align:middle line:90%
>>CARLSON: Yes.

00:26:26.670 --> 00:26:28.500 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: OK, from
the '70s, all right.

00:26:28.500 --> 00:26:32.500 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: It's showing up in
oxygen isotope analysis, which

00:26:32.500 --> 00:26:37.250 align:middle line:84%
is a proxy for temperature
change, the ratio of oxygen

00:26:37.250 --> 00:26:40.030 align:middle line:84%
18 to oxygen 16, and I won't
necessarily get into that,

00:26:40.030 --> 00:26:43.116 align:middle line:84%
but somebody can do
the research if they're

00:26:43.116 --> 00:26:44.740 align:middle line:84%
interested in finding
out how it works.

00:26:44.740 --> 00:26:47.440 align:middle line:84%
But during an ice age,
the heavier oxygen

00:26:47.440 --> 00:26:49.870 align:middle line:84%
is preferentially left
behind in the ocean water,

00:26:49.870 --> 00:26:52.460 align:middle line:84%
and it's the lighter oxygen
that's evaporated and gets

00:26:52.460 --> 00:26:54.330 align:middle line:90%
precipitated in snowfall.

00:26:54.330 --> 00:26:59.510 align:middle line:84%
And also, in the oceans itself
when the carbonate shell

00:26:59.510 --> 00:27:02.700 align:middle line:84%
bearing creatures create their
shells out of ocean water,

00:27:02.700 --> 00:27:06.260 align:middle line:84%
the ocean water carries the
imprint of that oxygen 18,

00:27:06.260 --> 00:27:08.820 align:middle line:90%
oxygen 16 ratio.

00:27:08.820 --> 00:27:10.990 align:middle line:84%
So from there,
scientists can now just

00:27:10.990 --> 00:27:14.210 align:middle line:84%
discern major temperature
changes, right?

00:27:14.210 --> 00:27:16.650 align:middle line:90%
Well, two things now happen.

00:27:16.650 --> 00:27:21.010 align:middle line:84%
In the early '70s, once they
realized that the ice mostly

00:27:21.010 --> 00:27:23.644 align:middle line:84%
was gone in less,
day, than 7,000 years,

00:27:23.644 --> 00:27:25.060 align:middle line:84%
which is what they
were assuming--

00:27:25.060 --> 00:27:26.660 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Rather than
millions of years.

00:27:26.660 --> 00:27:27.920 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: Or hundreds
of thousands of years.

00:27:27.920 --> 00:27:28.460 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Hundreds
of thousands, yes.

00:27:28.460 --> 00:27:30.370 align:middle line:90%
>>CARLSON: Right, right.

00:27:30.370 --> 00:27:32.670 align:middle line:84%
They were faced
with a conundrum.

00:27:32.670 --> 00:27:34.180 align:middle line:90%
And it was this.

00:27:34.180 --> 00:27:38.060 align:middle line:84%
In order to melt ice, it
takes heat energy, right?

00:27:38.060 --> 00:27:43.820 align:middle line:10%
And what they concluded was
that the amount of recession--

00:27:43.820 --> 00:27:46.220 align:middle line:10%
OK, if you've got this
huge ice mass that

00:27:46.220 --> 00:27:48.374 align:middle line:10%
covers half of North
America, and you're

00:27:48.374 --> 00:27:50.040 align:middle line:10%
going to get rid of
it, and let's assume

00:27:50.040 --> 00:27:51.740 align:middle line:10%
it starts melting
back, just like we

00:27:51.740 --> 00:27:54.840 align:middle line:10%
saw glaciers melting back
during the Little Ice Age,

00:27:54.840 --> 00:27:58.480 align:middle line:10%
what they realized was that
roughly 800 feet of ice

00:27:58.480 --> 00:28:05.180 align:middle line:10%
had to melt back every year
nonstop for 5,000 years.

00:28:05.180 --> 00:28:08.930 align:middle line:84%
And they calculated the amount
of energy needed to do that.

00:28:08.930 --> 00:28:11.080 align:middle line:84%
And for the
physicists out there,

00:28:11.080 --> 00:28:18.770 align:middle line:84%
we say it's 360 kilocalories
per square centimeter per year.

00:28:18.770 --> 00:28:20.900 align:middle line:84%
And they said, OK, well,
what's available in Canada

00:28:20.900 --> 00:28:26.820 align:middle line:84%
now where there is no
gigantic ice cap, right?

00:28:26.820 --> 00:28:29.670 align:middle line:84%
Just like we're seeing this
snowfall outside right now,

00:28:29.670 --> 00:28:32.210 align:middle line:84%
but come warm weather,
that snowfall melts.

00:28:32.210 --> 00:28:36.010 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't accumulate
as glacial ice, does it?

00:28:36.010 --> 00:28:39.630 align:middle line:84%
So here's what they
were confronted with.

00:28:39.630 --> 00:28:42.730 align:middle line:84%
What's available in Canada
right now to melt ice

00:28:42.730 --> 00:28:47.640 align:middle line:84%
was only a fraction
of 360 kilocalories

00:28:47.640 --> 00:28:49.310 align:middle line:90%
per square centimeter per year.

00:28:49.310 --> 00:28:51.860 align:middle line:90%


00:28:51.860 --> 00:28:54.230 align:middle line:84%
Well, they looked around,
and they said, well,

00:28:54.230 --> 00:28:56.255 align:middle line:90%
what's available on Earth today?

00:28:56.255 --> 00:28:57.880 align:middle line:84%
They looked at tropical
oceans and they

00:28:57.880 --> 00:29:00.500 align:middle line:90%
looked at African deserts.

00:29:00.500 --> 00:29:03.760 align:middle line:84%
And they said, OK, what's
available in African deserts

00:29:03.760 --> 00:29:05.090 align:middle line:90%
to melt?

00:29:05.090 --> 00:29:07.020 align:middle line:84%
How much heat
energy is available?

00:29:07.020 --> 00:29:10.990 align:middle line:84%
And it worked out to be
about 250 kilocalories

00:29:10.990 --> 00:29:12.520 align:middle line:90%
per square centimeter per year.

00:29:12.520 --> 00:29:15.367 align:middle line:84%
So African deserts
were only about 2/3

00:29:15.367 --> 00:29:16.825 align:middle line:84%
of the amount of
energy available--

00:29:16.825 --> 00:29:18.620 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: That would be
required to melt at that rate.

00:29:18.620 --> 00:29:19.911 align:middle line:90%
>>CARLSON: You got it, exactly.

00:29:19.911 --> 00:29:25.290 align:middle line:84%
And now, the heat of an African
desert applied to the ice cap

00:29:25.290 --> 00:29:31.920 align:middle line:84%
directly for 5,000, 6,000 years,
so what they came up with was

00:29:31.920 --> 00:29:34.440 align:middle line:84%
they called it the
energy paradox.

00:29:34.440 --> 00:29:36.292 align:middle line:84%
And they struggled with
it for three years.

00:29:36.292 --> 00:29:37.750 align:middle line:84%
There's another
conference, I think

00:29:37.750 --> 00:29:40.712 align:middle line:84%
it was in 1975 or '76,
where they've come back

00:29:40.712 --> 00:29:41.920 align:middle line:90%
and they're addressing again.

00:29:41.920 --> 00:29:44.710 align:middle line:84%
And they give up, and
they said basically, there

00:29:44.710 --> 00:29:46.660 align:middle line:84%
must be an error in
the data somewhere.

00:29:46.660 --> 00:29:48.290 align:middle line:84%
We'll put it on the
shelf and get back

00:29:48.290 --> 00:29:50.930 align:middle line:90%
to it, which they haven't done.

00:29:50.930 --> 00:29:54.630 align:middle line:84%
But in the interim, of course,
the actual amount of time,

00:29:54.630 --> 00:29:57.240 align:middle line:84%
nobody had identified
catastrophic rise events

00:29:57.240 --> 00:29:59.190 align:middle line:90%
at that point, you see.

00:29:59.190 --> 00:30:03.470 align:middle line:84%
Now, fast forward 20
years to the early '90s,

00:30:03.470 --> 00:30:07.770 align:middle line:84%
and we have two expeditions to
Greenland, one European, one

00:30:07.770 --> 00:30:08.960 align:middle line:90%
American.

00:30:08.960 --> 00:30:12.520 align:middle line:84%
Over five seasons,
they extracted cores

00:30:12.520 --> 00:30:15.120 align:middle line:84%
at the summit of the
Greenland ice sheet

00:30:15.120 --> 00:30:16.765 align:middle line:90%
all the way down to bedrock.

00:30:16.765 --> 00:30:18.260 align:middle line:84%
They pull out those
cores, and they

00:30:18.260 --> 00:30:21.260 align:middle line:84%
can look at the year-by-year
layering of glacial ice.

00:30:21.260 --> 00:30:25.990 align:middle line:84%
And then they can analyze the
constituents of those layers.

00:30:25.990 --> 00:30:30.450 align:middle line:84%
And it's the dust content,
the gaseous content

00:30:30.450 --> 00:30:32.440 align:middle line:90%
in entrained air bubbles.

00:30:32.440 --> 00:30:35.340 align:middle line:90%
It's the oxygen isotope content.

00:30:35.340 --> 00:30:38.530 align:middle line:84%
And from that, they can
discern a lot of things

00:30:38.530 --> 00:30:43.170 align:middle line:84%
about the ambient climate,
just like dendrochronologists

00:30:43.170 --> 00:30:48.010 align:middle line:84%
can look at tree rings and can
discern, extract information

00:30:48.010 --> 00:30:49.484 align:middle line:90%
about the ambient climate.

00:30:49.484 --> 00:30:50.900 align:middle line:84%
Was there a lot
of rain that year,

00:30:50.900 --> 00:30:53.370 align:middle line:90%
was there a drought, et cetera?

00:30:53.370 --> 00:30:57.580 align:middle line:84%
What they realized was that
there were two enormous warming

00:30:57.580 --> 00:31:02.260 align:middle line:84%
spikes bracketing this
Younger Dryas period.

00:31:02.260 --> 00:31:05.330 align:middle line:84%
The first one seemed
to be the most intense.

00:31:05.330 --> 00:31:07.850 align:middle line:84%
And they dated it at
somewhere between like 13,000

00:31:07.850 --> 00:31:10.260 align:middle line:90%
to 14,000 years ago.

00:31:10.260 --> 00:31:16.960 align:middle line:84%
OK, so picture now, the glaciers
start receding normally.

00:31:16.960 --> 00:31:19.480 align:middle line:84%
This could be the result
of the changing geometries

00:31:19.480 --> 00:31:21.640 align:middle line:84%
between the Earth
and the sun, what are

00:31:21.640 --> 00:31:24.870 align:middle line:90%
called the Milankovitch forces.

00:31:24.870 --> 00:31:26.580 align:middle line:84%
Because through the
changing geometries

00:31:26.580 --> 00:31:29.750 align:middle line:84%
of the Earth and the sun,
it changes the amount

00:31:29.750 --> 00:31:33.310 align:middle line:84%
of incidental solar
radiation that

00:31:33.310 --> 00:31:37.710 align:middle line:84%
reaches the surface
of the Earth, right?

00:31:37.710 --> 00:31:40.230 align:middle line:84%
If you increase the amount
of solar radiation somewhat,

00:31:40.230 --> 00:31:41.670 align:middle line:84%
the glaciers are
going to shrink.

00:31:41.670 --> 00:31:43.820 align:middle line:84%
If you decrease the
amount of solar radiation,

00:31:43.820 --> 00:31:46.016 align:middle line:84%
glaciers are going
to expand, right?

00:31:46.016 --> 00:31:47.910 align:middle line:90%
Well, so everything looks good.

00:31:47.910 --> 00:31:49.170 align:middle line:90%
It looks normal, right?

00:31:49.170 --> 00:31:52.480 align:middle line:84%
15,000 to 13,000 years ago
the glaciers start shrinking,

00:31:52.480 --> 00:31:56.710 align:middle line:84%
but then 13,000 years ago
that nice leisurely pace

00:31:56.710 --> 00:32:01.410 align:middle line:84%
is interrupted by this
massive spasm of warming

00:32:01.410 --> 00:32:06.440 align:middle line:84%
and concomitant
melting of the ice

00:32:06.440 --> 00:32:09.645 align:middle line:84%
and the first catastrophic
rise in sea level that

00:32:09.645 --> 00:32:14.370 align:middle line:84%
is now being documented by
the marine geologists, right?

00:32:14.370 --> 00:32:19.330 align:middle line:84%
And then what happens is the
climate of the planet shifts

00:32:19.330 --> 00:32:23.320 align:middle line:84%
back into full glacial
mode equivalent to what

00:32:23.320 --> 00:32:26.280 align:middle line:90%
it had been 18,000 years ago.

00:32:26.280 --> 00:32:31.380 align:middle line:84%
For 1,300 years, it's in full,
deep, bitter glacial cold.

00:32:31.380 --> 00:32:34.360 align:middle line:84%
And then at 11,600
years ago, there's

00:32:34.360 --> 00:32:40.000 align:middle line:84%
a second massive warming
spike, a meltwater pulse 1b,

00:32:40.000 --> 00:32:42.250 align:middle line:84%
and in that interval
between those two

00:32:42.250 --> 00:32:45.165 align:middle line:84%
that all the great mega
fauna, the woolly mammoths,

00:32:45.165 --> 00:32:49.920 align:middle line:84%
the saber tooth cats, the giant
ground sloths, the cave bears,

00:32:49.920 --> 00:32:54.800 align:middle line:84%
120 roughly species
of giant mega mammal,

00:32:54.800 --> 00:32:57.460 align:middle line:84%
they all went extinct
within that window.

00:32:57.460 --> 00:33:01.490 align:middle line:84%
So the prevailing theory has
been for the last roughly half

00:33:01.490 --> 00:33:05.210 align:middle line:84%
century that Paleo-Indian
hunters were somehow

00:33:05.210 --> 00:33:08.930 align:middle line:84%
responsible, which I think
is a personally and utterly

00:33:08.930 --> 00:33:10.260 align:middle line:90%
ludicrous idea.

00:33:10.260 --> 00:33:12.210 align:middle line:84%
And the evidence
is now beginning

00:33:12.210 --> 00:33:18.160 align:middle line:84%
to emerge that the culture that
proceeded the event of 13,000

00:33:18.160 --> 00:33:20.890 align:middle line:84%
years ago, which is
called Clovis Culture,

00:33:20.890 --> 00:33:22.980 align:middle line:84%
underwent a near
extinction event as

00:33:22.980 --> 00:33:27.050 align:middle line:84%
well, that the whole Clovis
culture culture collapsed.

00:33:27.050 --> 00:33:29.070 align:middle line:84%
And those lines of evidence
that are converging

00:33:29.070 --> 00:33:36.750 align:middle line:84%
are based on radiocarbon dating
of prevalent cultural activity

00:33:36.750 --> 00:33:40.570 align:middle line:84%
in the horizons below
13,000 years ago,

00:33:40.570 --> 00:33:43.200 align:middle line:84%
and then it ends,
rock quarries that

00:33:43.200 --> 00:33:46.140 align:middle line:84%
had been quarried for
centuries that are now suddenly

00:33:46.140 --> 00:33:51.140 align:middle line:84%
abandoned, mythic assemblages,
which are the spear points

00:33:51.140 --> 00:33:53.040 align:middle line:84%
and tool kits and
so forth that are

00:33:53.040 --> 00:33:55.120 align:middle line:84%
abundant within the
stratigraphic record,

00:33:55.120 --> 00:33:58.180 align:middle line:84%
and then at 13,000 years
ago, they disappear.

00:33:58.180 --> 00:34:00.730 align:middle line:84%
And the same thing is
showing up now in Europe

00:34:00.730 --> 00:34:06.750 align:middle line:84%
as well, which is suggesting
that the human species may have

00:34:06.750 --> 00:34:10.060 align:middle line:90%
come very close to extinction.

00:34:10.060 --> 00:34:14.510 align:middle line:84%
We know that a lot of the great
mammals did become extinct.

00:34:14.510 --> 00:34:17.120 align:middle line:84%
As far as I know, no one
has seen a woolly mammoth

00:34:17.120 --> 00:34:19.850 align:middle line:90%
lately except in a museum.

00:34:19.850 --> 00:34:23.960 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And this also overlays
with Plato's description

00:34:23.960 --> 00:34:26.250 align:middle line:90%
of the ages when Atlantis--

00:34:26.250 --> 00:34:28.330 align:middle line:90%
>>CARLSON: Very good, yes.

00:34:28.330 --> 00:34:31.920 align:middle line:84%
Plato's places the
seismic event that

00:34:31.920 --> 00:34:35.480 align:middle line:84%
sunk Atlantis at
9,000 years prior

00:34:35.480 --> 00:34:38.199 align:middle line:90%
to Solon's exile in Egypt.

00:34:38.199 --> 00:34:42.730 align:middle line:84%
Well, Solon's exile in Egypt
took place right at 600 BC,

00:34:42.730 --> 00:34:45.070 align:middle line:90%
or 2,600 years ago.

00:34:45.070 --> 00:34:49.510 align:middle line:84%
2,600 plus 9,000
brings us to 11,600.

00:34:49.510 --> 00:34:52.010 align:middle line:84%
Now, coincidence
that Plato's date

00:34:52.010 --> 00:34:54.730 align:middle line:84%
exactly coincides with
what hard science has now

00:34:54.730 --> 00:34:58.810 align:middle line:84%
identified as being a major
climatic event that involved

00:34:58.810 --> 00:35:01.770 align:middle line:84%
a massive spike of
warming, a massive melting

00:35:01.770 --> 00:35:03.699 align:middle line:84%
event and a rapid
sea-level rise?

00:35:03.699 --> 00:35:05.490 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I would say
it's not coincidence.

00:35:05.490 --> 00:35:06.470 align:middle line:90%
>>CARLSON: Yeah, hardly.

00:35:06.470 --> 00:35:07.345 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Let me ask.

00:35:07.345 --> 00:35:10.950 align:middle line:84%
You're going back to the
carbon core samplings.

00:35:10.950 --> 00:35:16.940 align:middle line:84%
Are they able to measure the
solar radiation at all in that?

00:35:16.940 --> 00:35:20.840 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: Yes, through
beryllium deposits,

00:35:20.840 --> 00:35:23.827 align:middle line:84%
and that is something that I'm
only now beginning to explore.

00:35:23.827 --> 00:35:25.410 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Because
that seems like that

00:35:25.410 --> 00:35:26.618 align:middle line:90%
would be a really key factor.

00:35:26.618 --> 00:35:28.956 align:middle line:90%
>>CARLSON: Yes, yes, yes.

00:35:28.956 --> 00:35:30.330 align:middle line:84%
And like I said,
that's something

00:35:30.330 --> 00:35:32.000 align:middle line:84%
that I'm only now
beginning to explore.

00:35:32.000 --> 00:35:35.380 align:middle line:84%
But there seems to be a
growing mass of evidence

00:35:35.380 --> 00:35:37.002 align:middle line:90%
that yes, is showing.

00:35:37.002 --> 00:35:38.335 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Should be solar blast.

00:35:38.335 --> 00:35:41.030 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: Again,
solar variability.

00:35:41.030 --> 00:35:46.830 align:middle line:84%
But on the other hand,
in 2007 Richard Firestone

00:35:46.830 --> 00:35:50.760 align:middle line:84%
and his colleagues at
Lawrence Livermore laboratory

00:35:50.760 --> 00:35:54.210 align:middle line:84%
discovered that--
now, archaeologists

00:35:54.210 --> 00:35:56.790 align:middle line:84%
that had been looking
at these Clovis sites

00:35:56.790 --> 00:35:59.130 align:middle line:84%
had identified over
50 Clovis sites

00:35:59.130 --> 00:36:03.110 align:middle line:84%
around North America
and even some in Europe.

00:36:03.110 --> 00:36:06.230 align:middle line:84%
The culture that seems to be
very consistent with the North

00:36:06.230 --> 00:36:09.890 align:middle line:84%
American Clovis was
called the Solutrean, OK?

00:36:09.890 --> 00:36:14.570 align:middle line:84%
They had very almost identical
tool kits, cultural norms,

00:36:14.570 --> 00:36:16.150 align:middle line:90%
life ways, and so on.

00:36:16.150 --> 00:36:20.970 align:middle line:84%
OK, at the horizon where the
Clovis culture disappears

00:36:20.970 --> 00:36:24.030 align:middle line:84%
and where the great
mega mammals disappear

00:36:24.030 --> 00:36:27.050 align:middle line:84%
from the stratigraphic record,
there's quite frequently

00:36:27.050 --> 00:36:29.410 align:middle line:90%
a black carbonaceous layer.

00:36:29.410 --> 00:36:33.260 align:middle line:84%
They refer to it as the
black mat layer, right?

00:36:33.260 --> 00:36:34.630 align:middle line:90%
It's black.

00:36:34.630 --> 00:36:38.540 align:middle line:84%
The carbonaceous content is
primarily because of soot.

00:36:38.540 --> 00:36:40.035 align:middle line:90%
Soot would imply what?

00:36:40.035 --> 00:36:41.820 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: An eruption
of some kind.

00:36:41.820 --> 00:36:43.600 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: Well,
fire, things burning.

00:36:43.600 --> 00:36:49.660 align:middle line:84%
Actually, what it implies
is the burning biomass.

00:36:49.660 --> 00:36:51.990 align:middle line:84%
That's what it would
imply, forest fires,

00:36:51.990 --> 00:36:54.480 align:middle line:90%
things burning up.

00:36:54.480 --> 00:36:58.000 align:middle line:84%
Volcanic eruptions will
create layers of ash.

00:36:58.000 --> 00:37:02.560 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, there
are layers of ash.

00:37:02.560 --> 00:37:05.020 align:middle line:84%
And that's most likely
the result of the fact

00:37:05.020 --> 00:37:09.680 align:middle line:84%
that when you take 6 million
cubic miles of ice piled up

00:37:09.680 --> 00:37:13.180 align:middle line:84%
on the North American continent,
over the center that ice mass,

00:37:13.180 --> 00:37:15.340 align:middle line:90%
it's two miles thick.

00:37:15.340 --> 00:37:17.595 align:middle line:84%
I mean, that's really
hard to imagine.

00:37:17.595 --> 00:37:19.340 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Over 10,000
feet thick, yeah.

00:37:19.340 --> 00:37:21.110 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: Over
10,000 feet thick.

00:37:21.110 --> 00:37:23.870 align:middle line:84%
That tremendous weight
literally crushes

00:37:23.870 --> 00:37:26.980 align:middle line:84%
the crust of the earth
down into the mantle,

00:37:26.980 --> 00:37:30.360 align:middle line:84%
maybe as much as a
couple thousand feet.

00:37:30.360 --> 00:37:33.560 align:middle line:84%
When that ice is
released, it springs back.

00:37:33.560 --> 00:37:37.900 align:middle line:84%
That's called
isostatic rebound, OK?

00:37:37.900 --> 00:37:41.730 align:middle line:84%
The crust begins to come back
in this isostatic rebound.

00:37:41.730 --> 00:37:43.400 align:middle line:84%
At the same time,
you're removing

00:37:43.400 --> 00:37:46.260 align:middle line:84%
all of this mass
from the continent.

00:37:46.260 --> 00:37:49.330 align:middle line:84%
You're putting it back
into the ocean basins.

00:37:49.330 --> 00:37:52.780 align:middle line:84%
That causes
isostatic depression.

00:37:52.780 --> 00:37:57.010 align:middle line:84%
So what you basically have going
on with this rapid deglaciation

00:37:57.010 --> 00:38:02.799 align:middle line:84%
is an enormous mass transfer
on the crust of the earth.

00:38:02.799 --> 00:38:05.090 align:middle line:84%
Clearly there are going to
be two consequences of that,

00:38:05.090 --> 00:38:07.116 align:middle line:84%
both of which are
being well documented--

00:38:07.116 --> 00:38:08.490 align:middle line:84%
intense seismicity,
earthquakes--

00:38:08.490 --> 00:38:10.800 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yes, and
crust displacement.

00:38:10.800 --> 00:38:13.680 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: Crust
displacement, volcanism.

00:38:13.680 --> 00:38:17.310 align:middle line:84%
And both of those are
being documented as being,

00:38:17.310 --> 00:38:22.320 align:middle line:84%
I think, clearly secondary
consequences of this phenomena.

00:38:22.320 --> 00:38:23.670 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Interesting, OK.

00:38:23.670 --> 00:38:25.392 align:middle line:84%
So do you want to
continue on that?

00:38:25.392 --> 00:38:27.600 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: Insert something
if you've got a question.

00:38:27.600 --> 00:38:29.599 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well, I'm going
to ask a question now.

00:38:29.599 --> 00:38:33.010 align:middle line:84%
So with everything we talked
about in our last conversation,

00:38:33.010 --> 00:38:35.570 align:middle line:84%
with evidence left behind
by ancient cultures

00:38:35.570 --> 00:38:39.270 align:middle line:84%
in a universal language of
geometry, form, numbers,

00:38:39.270 --> 00:38:42.700 align:middle line:84%
letters, et cetera,
where is this indicated?

00:38:42.700 --> 00:38:44.460 align:middle line:84%
And I'm trying to
kind of steer you

00:38:44.460 --> 00:38:47.884 align:middle line:84%
towards some of the stories,
the least likely stories

00:38:47.884 --> 00:38:50.050 align:middle line:84%
that we would hear, even
in the form the fairy tales

00:38:50.050 --> 00:38:53.450 align:middle line:84%
and such, that might
embed this information.

00:38:53.450 --> 00:38:56.480 align:middle line:84%
And also let's talk
about our deep-seated

00:38:56.480 --> 00:39:01.787 align:middle line:84%
fear of annihilation and our
memory loss after this period.

00:39:01.787 --> 00:39:03.370 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: Starting
with that, I think

00:39:03.370 --> 00:39:05.130 align:middle line:84%
it's clear that
once we recognize

00:39:05.130 --> 00:39:08.450 align:middle line:84%
the reality of these
kinds of events,

00:39:08.450 --> 00:39:13.050 align:middle line:84%
in contrast to what we were
taught as schoolchildren

00:39:13.050 --> 00:39:15.950 align:middle line:84%
about the history of the
Earth, which was basically

00:39:15.950 --> 00:39:22.020 align:middle line:84%
a strict uniformity-- we
were taught, I was taught,

00:39:22.020 --> 00:39:23.440 align:middle line:84%
and most of us
were, to the extent

00:39:23.440 --> 00:39:25.840 align:middle line:84%
that we were made familiar
with Earth history

00:39:25.840 --> 00:39:29.307 align:middle line:84%
that geological change
happens one grain of sand

00:39:29.307 --> 00:39:30.640 align:middle line:90%
and one drop of water at a time.

00:39:30.640 --> 00:39:31.460 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: It's orderly.

00:39:31.460 --> 00:39:32.080 align:middle line:90%
It's slow.

00:39:32.080 --> 00:39:34.455 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: And over millions
of years, it can accumulate.

00:39:34.455 --> 00:39:35.900 align:middle line:90%
And this is certainly true.

00:39:35.900 --> 00:39:38.950 align:middle line:84%
Yes, over millions of
years, change accumulates,

00:39:38.950 --> 00:39:40.990 align:middle line:90%
yes, pretty remarkably, too.

00:39:40.990 --> 00:39:44.790 align:middle line:84%
However, what they were not
aware of and that we now know

00:39:44.790 --> 00:39:47.750 align:middle line:84%
is it that that orderly
pace of gradualistic change

00:39:47.750 --> 00:39:53.260 align:middle line:84%
is punctuated by these
catastrophic events.

00:39:53.260 --> 00:39:55.480 align:middle line:84%
I call them points
of discontinuity,

00:39:55.480 --> 00:40:02.010 align:middle line:84%
the non-linear phases within
that continuum of change.

00:40:02.010 --> 00:40:06.600 align:middle line:84%
And it's those, and the fact
that-- well, consider now

00:40:06.600 --> 00:40:08.920 align:middle line:84%
in the last 200,000
years, there may

00:40:08.920 --> 00:40:12.850 align:middle line:84%
have been four full
interglacial cycles

00:40:12.850 --> 00:40:15.200 align:middle line:90%
that have come and gone, right?

00:40:15.200 --> 00:40:19.040 align:middle line:84%
Each one of those could
have been very catastrophic.

00:40:19.040 --> 00:40:21.590 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, we now
know, documenting

00:40:21.590 --> 00:40:23.840 align:middle line:84%
going over the last couple
hundred thousand years,

00:40:23.840 --> 00:40:28.090 align:middle line:84%
there have been a
dozen or more episodes,

00:40:28.090 --> 00:40:33.050 align:middle line:84%
which, were they to occur
today, would seriously

00:40:33.050 --> 00:40:37.820 align:middle line:84%
stress modern civilization, if
not eliminate it altogether,

00:40:37.820 --> 00:40:40.690 align:middle line:84%
not necessarily cause the
extinction of human beings,

00:40:40.690 --> 00:40:44.107 align:middle line:84%
but basically cause the global
collapse of civilization.

00:40:44.107 --> 00:40:45.940 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: With a few
human beings scrambling

00:40:45.940 --> 00:40:47.020 align:middle line:90%
to caves for a while.

00:40:47.020 --> 00:40:49.150 align:middle line:90%
>>CARLSON: Exactly, exactly.

00:40:49.150 --> 00:40:52.470 align:middle line:84%
Now, the
anthropological evidence

00:40:52.470 --> 00:40:55.500 align:middle line:84%
shows us that
modern humans, just

00:40:55.500 --> 00:40:58.300 align:middle line:84%
like us, with the
same intelligence,

00:40:58.300 --> 00:41:00.550 align:middle line:84%
have been around-- and this
is a conservative number--

00:41:00.550 --> 00:41:02.830 align:middle line:84%
between 150,000
and 180,000 years.

00:41:02.830 --> 00:41:05.110 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going just on
the hard evidence of--

00:41:05.110 --> 00:41:06.830 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yeah, and
Michael Cremo's work,

00:41:06.830 --> 00:41:09.110 align:middle line:84%
for example, would take it
back to millions of years.

00:41:09.110 --> 00:41:10.990 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: Right, and
most anthropologists

00:41:10.990 --> 00:41:11.870 align:middle line:90%
are going to dispute that.

00:41:11.870 --> 00:41:12.250 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:41:12.250 --> 00:41:14.790 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: But we don't need
to go there to make the point.

00:41:14.790 --> 00:41:16.960 align:middle line:84%
Even if we go back
180,000 years,

00:41:16.960 --> 00:41:20.400 align:middle line:84%
and we have modern skeletons
now that have been found,

00:41:20.400 --> 00:41:23.470 align:middle line:84%
documented, and dated
at 180,000 years.

00:41:23.470 --> 00:41:27.490 align:middle line:84%
If we think of a human
generation as being 25 years,

00:41:27.490 --> 00:41:31.250 align:middle line:84%
that's 7,000 generations
of humans, right?

00:41:31.250 --> 00:41:33.980 align:middle line:84%
Now, in 180,000
years, like I said,

00:41:33.980 --> 00:41:38.140 align:middle line:84%
there has been probably
a dozen or more events,

00:41:38.140 --> 00:41:40.440 align:middle line:84%
which if they were
to recur today,

00:41:40.440 --> 00:41:44.400 align:middle line:84%
could cause mass mortality,
serious stressing

00:41:44.400 --> 00:41:48.310 align:middle line:84%
of modern civilization, even
to the point of extinction

00:41:48.310 --> 00:41:51.790 align:middle line:84%
of modern civilization,
basically pulling the plug.

00:41:51.790 --> 00:41:55.670 align:middle line:84%
Because modern civilization is
now so interconnected, right?

00:41:55.670 --> 00:41:59.840 align:middle line:84%
If we have a Katrina, as
an example, that wipes out

00:41:59.840 --> 00:42:03.950 align:middle line:84%
a large part of one city,
that's only one small part

00:42:03.950 --> 00:42:06.830 align:middle line:84%
of the intact
infrastructure, right?

00:42:06.830 --> 00:42:09.060 align:middle line:84%
If we go an order of
magnitude above that

00:42:09.060 --> 00:42:11.509 align:middle line:84%
and say we wipe out
10 major cities,

00:42:11.509 --> 00:42:13.050 align:middle line:84%
well, we're going
to recover from it,

00:42:13.050 --> 00:42:15.980 align:middle line:84%
but it's going to cause
serious economic ripples,

00:42:15.980 --> 00:42:18.030 align:middle line:84%
global economic
ripples that could

00:42:18.030 --> 00:42:21.280 align:middle line:84%
take a decade or
two to recover from.

00:42:21.280 --> 00:42:23.930 align:middle line:84%
If we go two orders
of magnitude,

00:42:23.930 --> 00:42:28.200 align:middle line:84%
now we're hovering on the
brink of global civilization

00:42:28.200 --> 00:42:29.480 align:middle line:90%
collapse.

00:42:29.480 --> 00:42:32.930 align:middle line:84%
Three orders of
magnitude, we're gone.

00:42:32.930 --> 00:42:35.430 align:middle line:84%
Civilization is
over as we know it.

00:42:35.430 --> 00:42:38.090 align:middle line:84%
Now, events can
be documented that

00:42:38.090 --> 00:42:40.020 align:middle line:90%
have occurred on that scale.

00:42:40.020 --> 00:42:41.040 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I was going to say
you've constructed a timeline.

00:42:41.040 --> 00:42:42.030 align:middle line:90%
>>CARLSON: Yes, I did.

00:42:42.030 --> 00:42:43.530 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: With these
various events.

00:42:43.530 --> 00:42:44.630 align:middle line:90%
>>CARLSON: Yes, I did.

00:42:44.630 --> 00:42:46.040 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: OK, and then
you show this little spot

00:42:46.040 --> 00:42:47.840 align:middle line:84%
at then end that
brings us up to now.

00:42:47.840 --> 00:42:49.170 align:middle line:90%
>>CARLSON: Yeah, yeah.

00:42:49.170 --> 00:42:51.090 align:middle line:90%
And there seems to be a tempo.

00:42:51.090 --> 00:42:53.610 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't seem like these
things are just distributed

00:42:53.610 --> 00:42:55.230 align:middle line:90%
randomly through time.

00:42:55.230 --> 00:42:57.560 align:middle line:84%
It appears that there is
a tempo to these things.

