astronomical sense.

00:44:53.480 --> 00:44:58.200 align:middle line:84%
Sphinx is a lion
and a man, right?

00:44:58.200 --> 00:45:00.850 align:middle line:84%
What does that suggest
within the zodiacal wheel?

00:45:00.850 --> 00:45:05.010 align:middle line:84%
Aquarius and Leo, this
axis that we're basically

00:45:05.010 --> 00:45:06.780 align:middle line:90%
transiting right now.

00:45:06.780 --> 00:45:10.730 align:middle line:84%
As the vernal equinox is moving
in the next few centuries,

00:45:10.730 --> 00:45:13.260 align:middle line:84%
over that point in the
zodiacal wheel where

00:45:13.260 --> 00:45:18.460 align:middle line:84%
we're looking across that great
cosmic circle at the other side

00:45:18.460 --> 00:45:22.080 align:middle line:84%
of that axis, and we see
that right there, boom,

00:45:22.080 --> 00:45:24.910 align:middle line:84%
the hammer came down and
something really, really

00:45:24.910 --> 00:45:26.960 align:middle line:90%
intense happen to this planet.

00:45:26.960 --> 00:45:28.600 align:middle line:90%
And it was intense.

00:45:28.600 --> 00:45:30.900 align:middle line:84%
As a barometer of
its intensity, we

00:45:30.900 --> 00:45:33.510 align:middle line:84%
can look at the loss of
species that occurred.

00:45:33.510 --> 00:45:36.660 align:middle line:84%
Because loss of species
is a direct indication

00:45:36.660 --> 00:45:40.440 align:middle line:90%
of loss of habitat, right?

00:45:40.440 --> 00:45:41.970 align:middle line:84%
The mass extinction
that occurred

00:45:41.970 --> 00:45:45.450 align:middle line:84%
at the end of the last ice age
is the greatest mass extinction

00:45:45.450 --> 00:45:47.980 align:middle line:84%
that has occurred on this
planet in 5 million years.

00:45:47.980 --> 00:45:50.690 align:middle line:84%
Basically what we had was
the mega mammals, which

00:45:50.690 --> 00:45:54.560 align:middle line:84%
are defined as any animal
over about 44 kilograms

00:45:54.560 --> 00:45:59.410 align:middle line:84%
or 100 pounds in body weight,
is defined as a mega mammal.

00:45:59.410 --> 00:46:02.547 align:middle line:10%
Roughly 120, depending on
how you define the species,

00:46:02.547 --> 00:46:04.630 align:middle line:10%
and there's a little bit
of difference of opinion,

00:46:04.630 --> 00:46:09.720 align:middle line:10%
but roughly 120 species met
their demise in that window,

00:46:09.720 --> 00:46:13.790 align:middle line:10%
the Younger Dryas window, that
transition out of the ice age,

00:46:13.790 --> 00:46:16.450 align:middle line:10%
which what a
geologist would call

00:46:16.450 --> 00:46:20.750 align:middle line:10%
the Pleistocene-Holocene
transition, right?

00:46:20.750 --> 00:46:23.710 align:middle line:84%
Now, the number of mega
mammal species on Earth

00:46:23.710 --> 00:46:26.170 align:middle line:90%
today is about that same number.

00:46:26.170 --> 00:46:30.220 align:middle line:84%
If we go back into the depths
of the ice age and then back

00:46:30.220 --> 00:46:32.570 align:middle line:84%
from there, tens of thousands,
hundreds of thousands

00:46:32.570 --> 00:46:34.630 align:middle line:84%
of years, for example,
in North America,

00:46:34.630 --> 00:46:38.140 align:middle line:84%
there were more large mammals
living in North America

00:46:38.140 --> 00:46:39.987 align:middle line:84%
than there are in the
Serengeti Plain today.

00:46:39.987 --> 00:46:41.070 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah, elephants.

00:46:41.070 --> 00:46:44.130 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: Yeah, there were
four species of proboscideans,

00:46:44.130 --> 00:46:46.390 align:middle line:90%
or elephants-- four.

00:46:46.390 --> 00:46:49.090 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, that's amazing
when you think about it.

00:46:49.090 --> 00:46:54.736 align:middle line:84%
The American Pleistocene lion,
which roamed around-- that

00:46:54.736 --> 00:46:55.860 align:middle line:90%
would have been right here.

00:46:55.860 --> 00:46:58.760 align:middle line:84%
I think they've found
specimens in Colorado.

00:46:58.760 --> 00:47:01.690 align:middle line:84%
It was nearly the size
of a horse, right?

00:47:01.690 --> 00:47:04.820 align:middle line:84%
The saber-toothed cat,
which everybody knows about.

00:47:04.820 --> 00:47:09.840 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And we see these
depicted symbolically

00:47:09.840 --> 00:47:12.900 align:middle line:84%
in myths and such and think,
wow, what an imagination.

00:47:12.900 --> 00:47:15.970 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: Yeah,
Graham just recently

00:47:15.970 --> 00:47:18.330 align:middle line:84%
emailed me a link
to what appears

00:47:18.330 --> 00:47:22.280 align:middle line:84%
to be a Stonehenge-like
structure 40

00:47:22.280 --> 00:47:24.980 align:middle line:84%
feet below the surface
of Lake Michigan.

00:47:24.980 --> 00:47:30.080 align:middle line:84%
And on one of the stones-- and
the photographs I've seen now

00:47:30.080 --> 00:47:32.910 align:middle line:84%
are fairly grainy--
but still, on one

00:47:32.910 --> 00:47:35.580 align:middle line:84%
of the stores it looks like
what is etched into the stone

00:47:35.580 --> 00:47:37.460 align:middle line:90%
is a carving of a mastodon.

00:47:37.460 --> 00:47:39.780 align:middle line:84%
Now, as it turns out,
there is a period

00:47:39.780 --> 00:47:42.000 align:middle line:84%
between 6,000 and
9,000 years ago

00:47:42.000 --> 00:47:45.550 align:middle line:84%
where Lake Michigan was perhaps
as much as 300 feet lower

00:47:45.550 --> 00:47:46.500 align:middle line:90%
than now.

00:47:46.500 --> 00:47:51.920 align:middle line:84%
So this area where this thing
