source of it was,

00:48:30.490 --> 00:48:33.470 align:middle line:84%
that seemed to imply that
perhaps mastadons might have

00:48:33.470 --> 00:48:35.290 align:middle line:84%
even been domesticated
to some extent,

00:48:35.290 --> 00:48:38.800 align:middle line:84%
like modern elephants, which
I find extremely fascinating.

00:48:38.800 --> 00:48:45.260 align:middle line:84%
But in any case, what we had was
we had profound global changes

00:48:45.260 --> 00:48:49.090 align:middle line:84%
that terminated the
2-million-year-plus period

00:48:49.090 --> 00:48:53.020 align:middle line:84%
of the Pleistocene and
inaugurated the Holocene,

00:48:53.020 --> 00:48:55.850 align:middle line:84%
which is the modern geological
epoch that we've been in.

00:48:55.850 --> 00:48:59.740 align:middle line:84%
And its inception is usually
given now in the textbooks

00:48:59.740 --> 00:49:02.430 align:middle line:90%
as 11,600 years ago.

00:49:02.430 --> 00:49:06.520 align:middle line:84%
And it's associated with a
rapid melting of the ice,

00:49:06.520 --> 00:49:08.590 align:middle line:84%
sudden rise in sea
level, and that's

00:49:08.590 --> 00:49:12.930 align:middle line:84%
when, by coincidence, Plato
says Atlantis was drowned.

00:49:12.930 --> 00:49:15.310 align:middle line:84%
Now, you remember what
I said about isostatcy,

00:49:15.310 --> 00:49:18.280 align:middle line:84%
this vertical movement
of the Earth's crust?

00:49:18.280 --> 00:49:22.990 align:middle line:84%
If you're rapidly dumping
hundreds of feet of ocean water

00:49:22.990 --> 00:49:26.747 align:middle line:84%
into the ocean basins where
the crust is the thinnest,

00:49:26.747 --> 00:49:29.080 align:middle line:84%
what do you think is going
to happen to the ocean bottom

00:49:29.080 --> 00:49:31.690 align:middle line:84%
to compensate for this
additional weight?

00:49:31.690 --> 00:49:32.510 align:middle line:90%
It's going to sink.

00:49:32.510 --> 00:49:33.880 align:middle line:90%
It's going to subside.

00:49:33.880 --> 00:49:37.021 align:middle line:84%
There's nothing
pseudoscientific about assuming

00:49:37.021 --> 00:49:38.520 align:middle line:84%
that there could
have been an island

00:49:38.520 --> 00:49:40.610 align:middle line:84%
complex in the
mid-Atlantic right

00:49:40.610 --> 00:49:44.240 align:middle line:84%
where Plato placed it,
that could have sunk.

00:49:44.240 --> 00:49:45.960 align:middle line:84%
Nothing pseudoscientific
about that.

00:49:45.960 --> 00:49:49.530 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: No, not
at all, and there

00:49:49.530 --> 00:49:51.710 align:middle line:84%
are people such as Edgar
Cayce, for example,

00:49:51.710 --> 00:49:54.990 align:middle line:84%
who gave their renderings in
more modern history, who also

00:49:54.990 --> 00:49:58.980 align:middle line:84%
said that within a period
close to our lifetimes,

00:49:58.980 --> 00:50:03.590 align:middle line:84%
we would start seeing the
rise of that continent again,

00:50:03.590 --> 00:50:06.690 align:middle line:84%
meaning there has to be some
kind of serious activity

00:50:06.690 --> 00:50:07.900 align:middle line:90%
going on for that to happen.

00:50:07.900 --> 00:50:10.245 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: He might have
meant that metaphorically.

00:50:10.245 --> 00:50:13.120 align:middle line:84%
Either way, even if
was metaphorically--

00:50:13.120 --> 00:50:17.016 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I think it was
literally, but yeah, go ahead.

00:50:17.016 --> 00:50:19.330 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: Well, in the
sense that, yeah, Atlantis

00:50:19.330 --> 00:50:20.940 align:middle line:84%
is going to rise
again in the sense

00:50:20.940 --> 00:50:23.420 align:middle line:84%
that we're now in
a position where

00:50:23.420 --> 00:50:27.240 align:middle line:84%
we can actually scientifically
verify Plato's account.

00:50:27.240 --> 00:50:29.010 align:middle line:84%
And Plato's account
is very detailed

00:50:29.010 --> 00:50:33.100 align:middle line:84%
in terms of its geography
and its geology and so on.

00:50:33.100 --> 00:50:35.320 align:middle line:84%
And if you go through,
like I have done,

00:50:35.320 --> 00:50:38.430 align:middle line:84%
line by line by line,
what you'll find

00:50:38.430 --> 00:50:41.860 align:middle line:84%
is that it all syncs up with
what we now know about geology.

00:50:41.860 --> 00:50:43.910 align:middle line:84%
And there is hard
scientific evidence

00:50:43.910 --> 00:50:46.510 align:middle line:84%
that along the
mid-Atlantic Ridge

00:50:46.510 --> 00:50:50.150 align:middle line:84%
there is a sunken, what they
call a microcontinent, which

00:50:50.150 --> 00:50:54.460 align:middle line:84%
is just about the size that
Plato described for Atlantis.

00:50:54.460 --> 00:50:57.620 align:middle line:84%
And its there, and it has a
great mountain range on it,

00:50:57.620 --> 00:50:59.160 align:middle line:90%
just like Plato described.

00:50:59.160 --> 00:51:02.600 align:middle line:84%
And the tips of those mountains
are the Azores Islands,

00:51:02.600 --> 00:51:03.290 align:middle line:90%
which is where--

00:51:03.290 --> 00:51:03.790 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: That's right.

00:51:03.790 --> 00:51:06.160 align:middle line:84%
Mount Pico is supposed
to be the remnant of it,

00:51:06.160 --> 00:51:07.460 align:middle line:90%
and it still remains visible.

00:51:07.460 --> 00:51:07.960 align:middle line:90%
It's there.

00:51:07.960 --> 00:51:08.668 align:middle line:90%
You can go to it.

00:51:08.668 --> 00:51:11.650 align:middle line:90%
>>CARLSON: Yes, yes.

00:51:11.650 --> 00:51:15.620 align:middle line:84%
The 400-foot rise in sea level,
post-glacial 400-foot rise

00:51:15.620 --> 00:51:20.895 align:middle line:84%
in sea level, roughly
reduce those islands to 50%.

00:51:20.895 --> 00:51:24.100 align:middle line:84%
But when you add and
the fact that there

00:51:24.100 --> 00:51:28.780 align:middle line:84%
had to be isostatic
compensation that occurred

00:51:28.780 --> 00:51:33.690 align:middle line:84%
in the form of the ocean
bottom literally dropping,

00:51:33.690 --> 00:51:36.170 align:middle line:84%
and if it's comparable to
what we see the rise over--

00:51:36.170 --> 00:51:38.040 align:middle line:84%
if you go up by
Hudson Bay, which

00:51:38.040 --> 00:51:40.080 align:middle line:84%
was the center of
the great ice sheet,

00:51:40.080 --> 00:51:42.740 align:middle line:84%
you can see shorelines
that are 1,000, 1,200.

00:51:42.740 --> 00:51:46.360 align:middle line:90%
1,500 feet above sea level.

00:51:46.360 --> 00:51:50.440 align:middle line:84%
Now, you take that and
add that to the 400 feet,

00:51:50.440 --> 00:51:52.250 align:middle line:84%
we're talking about
potentially thousands

00:51:52.250 --> 00:51:58.390 align:middle line:84%
of feet between sea level
change and the ocean bottom.

00:51:58.390 --> 00:52:02.260 align:middle line:84%
Now, it could very well be that
when we adjust for all of that,

00:52:02.260 --> 00:52:06.680 align:middle line:84%
that the entire microcontinent
of the Azores Plateau

00:52:06.680 --> 00:52:09.060 align:middle line:90%
may have been above water.

00:52:09.060 --> 00:52:11.270 align:middle line:84%
And interestingly,
there is documentation

00:52:11.270 --> 00:52:14.990 align:middle line:84%
that the Gulf Stream
during the ice age

00:52:14.990 --> 00:52:18.547 align:middle line:84%
diverted south just north
of the Azores plateau.

00:52:18.547 --> 00:52:19.630 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Oh, interesting.

00:52:19.630 --> 00:52:21.463 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: So you've
got the Azores Plateau.

00:52:21.463 --> 00:52:24.890 align:middle line:84%
Instead of going way up
here by the British Isles--

00:52:24.890 --> 00:52:25.510 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:52:25.510 --> 00:52:27.090 align:middle line:84%
>>CARLSON: Now,
if you're looking

00:52:27.090 --> 00:52:30.584 align:middle line:84%
for prime habitable real estate
during the ice age, that might

00:52:30.584 --> 00:52:31.750 align:middle line:90%
have been a very nice place.

00:52:31.750 --> 00:52:34.560 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: [LAUGHS] Yes, exactly.

00:52:34.560 --> 00:52:36.420 align:middle line:84%
Well, now there's
so many streams of

00:52:36.420 --> 00:52:38.000 align:middle line:90%
thought we can go into in this.

00:52:38.000 --> 00:52:41.660 align:middle line:84%
But what's interesting is
that as that was passed on,

00:52:41.660 --> 00:52:45.660 align:middle line:84%
as you say, from Egyptian
priests in ancient times

00:52:45.660 --> 00:52:49.060 align:middle line:84%
to Solon, Critias, down Plato
and so forth and then on

00:52:49.060 --> 00:52:52.630 align:middle line:84%
